 the 29 Mar review materials and repo docs instead of guessing.\n- Important correction: previous memory had overemphasized Telegram/watchdog context. The real active thread on 30 Mar was implementation planning/execution for the Content Factory editing department, especially PM -> VO -> S1 -> S2 architecture and Claude Code coordination.\n- PM (Production Manager) architecture was materially advanced today:\n  - We created canonical docs:\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_read_pub_contract.md`\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_override_contract.md\n\nSource: memory/2026-03-30.md#L1-L20","source":"memory","citation":"memory/2026-03-30.md#L1-L20"},{"path":"memory/2026-03-30.md","startLine":53,"endLine":76,"score":0.20457590222358701,"snippet":"- Canonical source for S1 is `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`; the workspace mirror is not reliable enough as source of truth.\n  - Canonical naming for this sector should be `b1_`, not `s1_`.\n  - S1 is already well-defined in docs as:\n    - `scene_director`\n    - `screenplay_validator`\n    - `tts_polish`\n    - `polish_validator`\n    - `scene_bible_builder`\n    - checkpoints by step\n  - `scene_bible.json` is the core output and should live at the run root as a living document.\n- Claude Code implemented S1 and passed tests, but there is an important durable nuance:\n  - The deterministic/runtime pieces are solid and reusable:\n    - validators\n    - scene_bible builder\n    - schema validat\n\nSource: memory/2026-03-30.md#L53-L76","source":"memory","citation":"memory/2026-03-30.md#L53-L76"}],"provider":"openai","model":"text-embedding-3-small","citations":"auto","mode":"hybrid"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978071040}}
{"type":"message","id":"be5971b6","parentId":"d9e4d938","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:27:56.139Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_l0Z12RRu4PM0vITYXKC9wJul|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc041c0b808193a9cf88a5a8ab7a05","name":"memory_get","arguments":{"path":"memory/2026-03-30.md","from":1,"lines":140},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"memory/2026-03-30.md\",\"from\":1,\"lines\":140}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_eBTIJBpJe8J5Vinl9cPnHlBb|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc041c0b98819383faead2c994e097","name":"sessions_list","arguments":{"limit":10,"messageLimit":3},"partialJson":"{\"limit\":10,\"messageLimit\":3}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2Dfk5ES9ocG6nosikit1fLx2|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc041c0ba0819385aadbf4f3c86683","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-31.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\\\\memory\\\\2026-03-31.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":2445,"output":104,"cacheRead":22016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24565,"cost":{"input":0.006112500000000001,"output":0.00156,"cacheRead":0.005503999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0131765}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774978072084,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0419753881939baba0c22c489664"}}
{"type":"message","id":"330751f6","parentId":"be5971b6","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:27:56.960Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_l0Z12RRu4PM0vITYXKC9wJul|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc041c0b808193a9cf88a5a8ab7a05","toolName":"memory_get","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"text\": \"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-30\\n\\n- Lucca accidentally reset the session; we reconstructed the relevant thread by reading the 29 Mar review materials and repo docs instead of guessing.\\n- Important correction: previous memory had overemphasized Telegram/watchdog context. The real active thread on 30 Mar was implementation planning/execution for the Content Factory editing department, especially PM -> VO -> S1 -> S2 architecture and Claude Code coordination.\\n- PM (Production Manager) architecture was materially advanced today:\\n  - We created canonical docs:\\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_read_pub_contract.md`\\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_override_contract.md`\\n  - We aligned PM mirror/docs around these contracts.\\n  - We standardized the Google service-account credential path for OpenClaw/runtime use as:\\n    - `C:\\\\secrets\\\\content_factory\\\\google_service_account.json`\\n  - Lucca confirmed the reused V3 service account has valid access to Sheets/Drive.\\n- Claude Code successfully implemented PM substrate v1 and then the override layer. Real outcomes:\\n  - PM can read the real PUB sheet, rank channels, support `auto_select`, `filtered_select`, `direct_select`, build canonical jobs, and validate them.\\n  - Real observed PUB state during testing:\\n    - 38 eligible channels\\n    - all with negative runway\\n    - `C001 PT` excluded because scripts are exhausted\\n    - `C004 FRA` was top urgency at runway `-17`\\n  - Durable principle confirmed: PM must treat PUB as operational truth, not strategic sovereignty; Tobias remains the upstream strategic layer.\\n- We intentionally formalized the PM operating modes as durable architecture:\\n  - `auto_select`\\n  - `filtered_select`\\n  - `direct_select`\\n  with authority order `direct_select > filtered_select > auto_select`.\\n  Critical rules:\\n  - `filtered_select` must not silently fall back to unrestricted auto mode.\\n  - `direct_select` must not silently choose another channel if the requested target is invalid.\\n- Claude Code successfully implemented VO minimal bootstrap on top of real PM jobs:\\n  - PM -> VO handoff works end-to-end.\\n  - VO creates runs under the canonical production root:\\n    - `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\production\\\\{account}_{language}\\\\{job_id}\\\\`\\n  - Policy chosen: if the run directory already exists, fail explicitly with `run_already_exists` (safe, deterministic, no silent merging).\\n  - VO bootstrap writes real artefacts like `job.json`, `run_metadata.json`, `checkpoints/vo_init.json`.\\n- We investigated V3 script fetch/lock behavior before designing the next VO step. Durable findings from `content_factory_v3`:\\n  - Script selection rule is simple and important: pick the first row with `Status = \\\"to do\\\"`.\\n  - Lock is applied by immediately updating sheet status to `processing`.\\n  - Legacy sheet columns in V3 are roughly:\\n    - `E = Status`\\n    - `F = Processing_Started`\\n    - `G = Processing_Completed`\\n    - `H = Account_Used`\\n  - This V3 semantics should be reused for the new VO rather than inventing a new lock system early.\\n- Claude Code then implemented `script_fetch_and_lock` successfully with real integrations:\\n  - PM -> VO -> script fetch & lock works end-to-end with real data.\\n  - Example real result:\\n    - `direct_select 004/fr`\\n    - script row 6 selected: `Les Enfants de la Creuse`\\n    - real sheet lock applied (`Status -> processing`)\\n    - local script artefacts written under `production/.../inputs/script/`\\n    - run ended at `next_step = ready_for_s1`\\n- S1 (Pre-Production) work advanced substantially. Important architectural findings:\\n  - Canonical source for S1 is `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`; the workspace mirror is not reliable enough as source of truth.\\n  - Canonical naming for this sector should be `b1_`, not `s1_`.\\n  - S1 is already well-defined in docs as:\\n    - `scene_director`\\n    - `screenplay_validator`\\n    - `tts_polish`\\n    - `polish_validator`\\n    - `scene_bible_builder`\\n    - checkpoints by step\\n  - `scene_bible.json` is the core output and should live at the run root as a living document.\\n- Claude Code implemented S1 and passed tests, but there is an important durable nuance:\\n  - The deterministic/runtime pieces are solid and reusable:\\n    - validators\\n    - scene_bible builder\\n    - schema validator\\n    - checkpoint writer\\n    - supervisor base\\n  - But the LLM operator steps (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`) were implemented as direct Python OpenAI API calls (`gpt-4.1-mini`) instead of real OpenClaw operators using the planned runtime (GPT-5.4 mini OAuth / Qwen local).\\n  - Therefore Tobias’ judgment is:\\n    - treat S1 as a **functional prototype accepted for pipeline validation**\\n    - not as final production-runtime architecture\\n  - We should preserve this distinction explicitly and not let the temporary Python direct-call mode become accidental production standard.\\n- Lucca agreed with the Tobias recommendation to accept S1 as a prototype-functional slice and move on to S2 while keeping the runtime-architecture debt explicit.\\n- S2 investigation produced durable architecture conclusions:\\n  - Canonical doc: `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`, but review shows the sector is split between two versions.\\n  - The more mature conceptual direction is:\\n    - `tts_generator`\\n    - `audio_transcriber`\\n    - `transcription/ratio validator`\\n    - `audio_validator` (LLM only for borderline cases)\\n    - `timestamp_aligner`\\n    - `bible_updater`\\n  - This is superior to the older `timing_extractor`-only model.\\n- Durable V3 findings for S2 / audio:\\n  - Gemini TTS in V3 is already implemented as a serious reusable substrate (`shared/services/gemini_tts_service.py`).\\n  - The TTS request is driven by:\\n    - text\\n    - explicit `language_code`\\n    - explicit `voice_name`\\n  - Voice choice should come exclusively from the channel YAML config in the new S2; no extra heuristic speaker selection.\\n  - KMS already manages key acquisition/reporting/cooldown/availability centrally; the TTS client should not reinvent that logic.\\n  - Client-side Gemini TTS code still appropriately handles call-specific behavior like hard timeouts, empty responses, content-block inference, and PCM->WAV packing.\\n- Durable V3 findings for WhisperX / validation / alignment:\\n  - WhisperX is managed as a local service that can be started/stopped/health-checked; Lucca says it stays off by default to avoid consuming GPU.\\n  - V3 has a mature `TranscriptionValidator` with language-specific thresholds, ignore patterns, exclude words, WER, and match ratio logic.\\n  - Example thresholds in V3 are language-specific and should strongly influence the new S2 (not a single universal threshold):\\n    - `en 0.60`, `fr 0.65`, `de 0.65`, `es 0.70`, `it 0.70`, `pt 0.75`, `ja 0.75`, `ko 0.75`, `ar 0.80`, `ru 0.82`, `pl 0.82`, default `0.85`.\\n  - V3 also already contains useful positional alignment logic using `SequenceMatcher` to transfer WhisperX timestamps back onto original script words when WhisperX mishears tokens (e.g. `911 -> 1091`). This is strong evidence that the new S2 should explicitly include `timestamp_aligner`, not just raw timestamp extraction.\\n- Durable architecture recommendation for S2 going forward:\\n  - TTS should allow controlled parallelism with a supervisor-level `TTS_CONCURRENCY_CAP`.\\n  - WhisperX should remain serialized / carefully controlled (GPU/local-service bound).\\n  - The likely OpenClaw-era layering for S2 is:\\n    - Python/runtime skills for:\\n      - `tts_generator`\\n      - `audio_transcriber`\\n      - `transcription_validator`\\n      - `timestamp_aligner`\\n      - `bible_updater`\\n    - one OpenClaw LLM operator only where it adds semantic judgment:\\n      - `audio_validator`\\n    - an `SM-S2` supervisor coordinating retries, parallelism, and checkpoints.\\n\",\n  \"path\": \"memory/2026-03-30.md\"\n}"}],"details":{"text":"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-30\n\n- Lucca accidentally reset the session; we reconstructed the relevant thread by reading the 29 Mar review materials and repo docs instead of guessing.\n- Important correction: previous memory had overemphasized Telegram/watchdog context. The real active thread on 30 Mar was implementation planning/execution for the Content Factory editing department, especially PM -> VO -> S1 -> S2 architecture and Claude Code coordination.\n- PM (Production Manager) architecture was materially advanced today:\n  - We created canonical docs:\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_read_pub_contract.md`\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_override_contract.md`\n  - We aligned PM mirror/docs around these contracts.\n  - We standardized the Google service-account credential path for OpenClaw/runtime use as:\n    - `C:\\secrets\\content_factory\\google_service_account.json`\n  - Lucca confirmed the reused V3 service account has valid access to Sheets/Drive.\n- Claude Code successfully implemented PM substrate v1 and then the override layer. Real outcomes:\n  - PM can read the real PUB sheet, rank channels, support `auto_select`, `filtered_select`, `direct_select`, build canonical jobs, and validate them.\n  - Real observed PUB state during testing:\n    - 38 eligible channels\n    - all with negative runway\n    - `C001 PT` excluded because scripts are exhausted\n    - `C004 FRA` was top urgency at runway `-17`\n  - Durable principle confirmed: PM must treat PUB as operational truth, not strategic sovereignty; Tobias remains the upstream strategic layer.\n- We intentionally formalized the PM operating modes as durable architecture:\n  - `auto_select`\n  - `filtered_select`\n  - `direct_select`\n  with authority order `direct_select > filtered_select > auto_select`.\n  Critical rules:\n  - `filtered_select` must not silently fall back to unrestricted auto mode.\n  - `direct_select` must not silently choose another channel if the requested target is invalid.\n- Claude Code successfully implemented VO minimal bootstrap on top of real PM jobs:\n  - PM -> VO handoff works end-to-end.\n  - VO creates runs under the canonical production root:\n    - `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\production\\{account}_{language}\\{job_id}\\`\n  - Policy chosen: if the run directory already exists, fail explicitly with `run_already_exists` (safe, deterministic, no silent merging).\n  - VO bootstrap writes real artefacts like `job.json`, `run_metadata.json`, `checkpoints/vo_init.json`.\n- We investigated V3 script fetch/lock behavior before designing the next VO step. Durable findings from `content_factory_v3`:\n  - Script selection rule is simple and important: pick the first row with `Status = \"to do\"`.\n  - Lock is applied by immediately updating sheet status to `processing`.\n  - Legacy sheet columns in V3 are roughly:\n    - `E = Status`\n    - `F = Processing_Started`\n    - `G = Processing_Completed`\n    - `H = Account_Used`\n  - This V3 semantics should be reused for the new VO rather than inventing a new lock system early.\n- Claude Code then implemented `script_fetch_and_lock` successfully with real integrations:\n  - PM -> VO -> script fetch & lock works end-to-end with real data.\n  - Example real result:\n    - `direct_select 004/fr`\n    - script row 6 selected: `Les Enfants de la Creuse`\n    - real sheet lock applied (`Status -> processing`)\n    - local script artefacts written under `production/.../inputs/script/`\n    - run ended at `next_step = ready_for_s1`\n- S1 (Pre-Production) work advanced substantially. Important architectural findings:\n  - Canonical source for S1 is `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`; the workspace mirror is not reliable enough as source of truth.\n  - Canonical naming for this sector should be `b1_`, not `s1_`.\n  - S1 is already well-defined in docs as:\n    - `scene_director`\n    - `screenplay_validator`\n    - `tts_polish`\n    - `polish_validator`\n    - `scene_bible_builder`\n    - checkpoints by step\n  - `scene_bible.json` is the core output and should live at the run root as a living document.\n- Claude Code implemented S1 and passed tests, but there is an important durable nuance:\n  - The deterministic/runtime pieces are solid and reusable:\n    - validators\n    - scene_bible builder\n    - schema validator\n    - checkpoint writer\n    - supervisor base\n  - But the LLM operator steps (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`) were implemented as direct Python OpenAI API calls (`gpt-4.1-mini`) instead of real OpenClaw operators using the planned runtime (GPT-5.4 mini OAuth / Qwen local).\n  - Therefore Tobias’ judgment is:\n    - treat S1 as a **functional prototype accepted for pipeline validation**\n    - not as final production-runtime architecture\n  - We should preserve this distinction explicitly and not let the temporary Python direct-call mode become accidental production standard.\n- Lucca agreed with the Tobias recommendation to accept S1 as a prototype-functional slice and move on to S2 while keeping the runtime-architecture debt explicit.\n- S2 investigation produced durable architecture conclusions:\n  - Canonical doc: `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`, but review shows the sector is split between two versions.\n  - The more mature conceptual direction is:\n    - `tts_generator`\n    - `audio_transcriber`\n    - `transcription/ratio validator`\n    - `audio_validator` (LLM only for borderline cases)\n    - `timestamp_aligner`\n    - `bible_updater`\n  - This is superior to the older `timing_extractor`-only model.\n- Durable V3 findings for S2 / audio:\n  - Gemini TTS in V3 is already implemented as a serious reusable substrate (`shared/services/gemini_tts_service.py`).\n  - The TTS request is driven by:\n    - text\n    - explicit `language_code`\n    - explicit `voice_name`\n  - Voice choice should come exclusively from the channel YAML config in the new S2; no extra heuristic speaker selection.\n  - KMS already manages key acquisition/reporting/cooldown/availability centrally; the TTS client should not reinvent that logic.\n  - Client-side Gemini TTS code still appropriately handles call-specific behavior like hard timeouts, empty responses, content-block inference, and PCM->WAV packing.\n- Durable V3 findings for WhisperX / validation / alignment:\n  - WhisperX is managed as a local service that can be started/stopped/health-checked; Lucca says it stays off by default to avoid consuming GPU.\n  - V3 has a mature `TranscriptionValidator` with language-specific thresholds, ignore patterns, exclude words, WER, and match ratio logic.\n  - Example thresholds in V3 are language-specific and should strongly influence the new S2 (not a single universal threshold):\n    - `en 0.60`, `fr 0.65`, `de 0.65`, `es 0.70`, `it 0.70`, `pt 0.75`, `ja 0.75`, `ko 0.75`, `ar 0.80`, `ru 0.82`, `pl 0.82`, default `0.85`.\n  - V3 also already contains useful positional alignment logic using `SequenceMatcher` to transfer WhisperX timestamps back onto original script words when WhisperX mishears tokens (e.g. `911 -> 1091`). This is strong evidence that the new S2 should explicitly include `timestamp_aligner`, not just raw timestamp extraction.\n- Durable architecture recommendation for S2 going forward:\n  - TTS should allow controlled parallelism with a supervisor-level `TTS_CONCURRENCY_CAP`.\n  - WhisperX should remain serialized / carefully controlled (GPU/local-service bound).\n  - The likely OpenClaw-era layering for S2 is:\n    - Python/runtime skills for:\n      - `tts_generator`\n      - `audio_transcriber`\n      - `transcription_validator`\n      - `timestamp_aligner`\n      - `bible_updater`\n    - one OpenClaw LLM operator only where it adds semantic judgment:\n      - `audio_validator`\n    - an `SM-S2` supervisor coordinating retries, parallelism, and checkpoints.\n","path":"memory/2026-03-30.md"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978076820}}
