IDENTITY.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_qXufYwvGRVSZCKncMbmuYxhb|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab280819388ebdacaceb28423","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\sm_s1_pre_production\\WORKFLOW.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\sm_s1_pre_production\\\\WORKFLOW.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_QVqjImVwVtxsinJshm98kCFY|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2848193b79e348eb993fbad","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\sm_s1_pre_production\\STATE.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\sm_s1_pre_production\\\\STATE.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_nXZLsWoYS3xWMRI9Kc3meIYk|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2888193a4c6f5f958b68e20","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\PROMPT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\PROMPT.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_JP5PvzIGjQ2q4wUbk6rlw8LW|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2908193b94a89e813296aba","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\PROMPT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish\\\\PROMPT.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":299,"output":364,"cacheRead":116224,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":116887,"cost":{"input":0.0007475,"output":0.0054600000000000004,"cacheRead":0.029056,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.035263499999999996}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774978770024,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06d299548193a3bdd89e446ff922"}}
{"type":"message","id":"ffb3c687","parentId":"2ed0d64d","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:41.832Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_QmLccf7yCeZPLHr72rN5yfDM|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2608193a9413e295cdcf24c","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Supervisor Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and first deterministic skill of the S1 (Pre-Production) Supervisor._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-30_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is the supervisory layer for Pre-Production.\n\nIts job is to take a run that is `ready_for_s1` and coordinate the sector until it produces:\n- `screenplay.json`\n- `screenplay_validation.json`\n- `tts_polished.json`\n- `polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nThe supervisor is an **OpenClaw LLM supervisor**, not a purely conversational helper and not a monolithic Python script that absorbs all work itself.\n\nIt should supervise using:\n- deterministic Python skills\n- specialized operators/sub-agents\n- explicit file contracts\n\n---\n\n## Core principle\n\n### Supervisor = brain\n### Skills = hands\n### Operators = specialists\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- decide the order of operations\n- decide when to call an operator vs a deterministic skill\n- interpret validation results\n- decide retry / fail / continue\n- write or trigger checkpoints\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should **not** directly absorb:\n- semantic scene generation\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path mechanics\n- deterministic validation logic\n- JSON merge/reindex mechanics\n\nThose belong to:\n- S1 operators (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`)\n- deterministic supervisor skills\n\n---\n\n## Current operator model\n\nThe current intended operator structure for S1 is:\n- `scene_director` -> OpenClaw operator\n- `tts_polish` -> OpenClaw operator\n\nThese operators communicate with the supervisor via explicit file contracts:\n- supervisor prepares input payload/file\n- operator reads input\n- operator writes output file\n- supervisor validates and decides next step\n\n## Controlled parallelism policy\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should support controlled parallelism for batchable operators.\n\n### Initial recommended concurrency caps\n- `scene_director_concurrency_cap = 2`\n- `tts_polish_concurrency_cap = 4`\n\n### Parallelism rules\n- only batchable operators should be parallelized\n- validators, mergers, builders, and preflight remain sequential/deterministic\n- the supervisor should not launch all batches at once without a cap\n- batches should be processed in controlled waves/windows\n- failed batches should be retried selectively when possible via `retry_planner`\n\n---\n\n## Current deterministic skills owned by the supervisor\n\n### Implemented now\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Newly required / now being formalized\n- `scene_director_output_validator`\n\n### Expected next skills\n- `checkpoint_writer` (already exists in `runtime/s1/checkpoint_writer.py`, pending light alignment audit only)\n\nThis list may evolve, but the supervisor should remain supervisory rather than mechanically overloaded.\n\n---\n\n## File contract principle\n\nThe supervisor must operate on persisted run artifacts.\n\nMinimum expected inputs before S1 begins:\n- `job.json`\n- `run_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_raw.txt`\n- `inputs/script/script_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_lock.json`\n- `checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json`\n\nMinimum expected outputs after S1 completes:\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step1_screenplay.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step2_screenplay_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step3_tts_polished.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step4_polish_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step5_scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_complete.json`\n\n---\n\n## First implemented supervisor skill: `s1_preflight_checker`\n\n### Purpose\nValidate that a run is structurally ready to enter S1 before any operator or semantic step is invoked.\n\n### Scope\nChecks:\n- run root exists\n- required input files exist\n- `job.json` is readable and contains `job_id`, `account`, `language`\n- channel config exists at `accounts/{account}/{language}.yaml`\n- `script_raw.txt` is readable and not empty\n- `vo_script_ready` checkpoint exists\n- run state is minimally compatible with entering S1\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_preflight_checker` does **not**:\n- create sector outputs\n- call operators\n- validate screenplay semantics\n- decide batching\n- modify the run\n\n### Input shape\n```json\n{\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\"\n}\n```\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"job\": {\n    \"job_id\": \"2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n    \"account\": \"004\",\n    \"language\": \"fr\"\n  },\n  \"paths\": {\n    \"job_json\": \".../job.json\",\n    \"run_metadata\": \".../run_metadata.json\",\n    \"script_raw\": \".../inputs/script/script_raw.txt\",\n    \"script_metadata\": \".../inputs/script/script_metadata.json\",\n    \"script_lock\": \".../inputs/script/script_lock.json\",\n    \"vo_script_ready_checkpoint\": \".../checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json\",\n    \"channel_config\": \".../accounts/004/fr.yaml\"\n  },\n  \"script_stats\": {\n    \"char_count\": 0,\n    \"word_count\": 0\n  },\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n### Error policy\nThe skill should collect all relevant failures and return them together.\nIt should not stop at the first missing file.\n\n### Warning policy\nExamples of warning-worthy but non-fatal conditions:\n- script very short\n- script very long\n- `b1_pre_production/` already exists but `b1_complete.json` does not\n\n### Fatal examples\n- missing `job.json`\n- missing `script_raw.txt`\n- unreadable or invalid `job.json`\n- missing channel config\n- missing `vo_script_ready.json`\n- empty script\n\n---\n\n## Naming convention\nThe canonical checkpoint and sector naming for Pre-Production is:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nThe older `s1_*` naming should not be treated as canonical.\n\n---\n\n## Second implemented supervisor skill: `s1_paths_resolver`\n\n### Purpose\nResolve and centralize the canonical S1 paths for the run.\n\n### Scope\nResolves and optionally creates the directory structure for:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_pre_production/inputs/`\n- `b1_pre_production/intermediate/`\n- `inputs/scene_director/`\n- `inputs/tts_polish/`\n- `intermediate/scene_director/`\n- `intermediate/tts_polish/`\n- canonical output file paths\n- canonical `b1_*` checkpoint file paths\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_paths_resolver` does **not**:\n- validate semantic readiness\n- call operators\n- inspect screenplay or polish content\n- perform batching\n\n### Input shape\n```json\n{\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"create_dirs\": true\n}\n```\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"created_dirs\": true,\n  \"paths\": {\n    \"b1_root\": \".../b1_pre_production\",\n    \"inputs_root\": \".../b1_pre_production/inputs\",\n    \"intermediate_root\": \".../b1_pre_production/intermediate\",\n    \"screenplay_path\": \".../b1_pre_production/screenplay.json\",\n    \"tts_polished_path\": \".../b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json\",\n    \"scene_bible_path\": \".../scene_bible.json\",\n    \"b1_complete_checkpoint\": \".../checkpoints/b1_complete.json\"\n  },\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n## Third implemented supervisor skill: `script_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nSplit the raw script into manageable work batches for `scene_director` without turning the supervisor into a monolithic batching script.\n\n### Scope\n- receives raw script text or script file path\n- plans batches using target/min/max word budgets\n- prefers paragraph boundaries\n- falls back to sentence-based splitting for oversized paragraphs\n- preserves order and emits a stable `sd_###` batch sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n`script_batch_planner` does **not**:\n- divide the script into final scenes\n- call `scene_director`\n- perform semantic validation\n- merge operator outputs\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target words per batch: `750`\n- minimum words per batch: `450`\n- maximum words per batch: `950`\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"total_words\": 3520,\n  \"batch_count\": 5,\n  \"target_words_per_batch\": 750,\n  \"min_words_per_batch\": 450,\n  \"max_words_per_batch\": 950,\n  \"batches\": [\n    {\n      \"batch_id\": \"sd_001\",\n      \"start_word\": 1,\n      \"end_word\": 742,\n      \"word_count\": 742,\n      \"text\": \"...\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n## Fourth implemented supervisor skill: `scene_director_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `scene_director` operator for each planned script batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives one script batch from `script_batch_planner`\n- injects `scene_words_range` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n`scene_director_io_adapter` does **not**:\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge batch outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Output contract principle\nEach batch payload should explicitly tell `scene_director`:\n- who the run/job is\n- what the batch text is\n- what scene structure is expected\n- where to write the result\n\n## Fifth implemented supervisor skill: `screenplay_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `scene_director` into one canonical `screenplay.json` without forcing the supervisor itself to concatenate, validate, and reindex scene objects manually.\n\nImportant precondition:\n`screenplay_merger` should only receive batch outputs that have already passed per-batch validation.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered batch output files\n- validates minimum required scene fields\n- concatenates scenes in batch order\n- reassigns canonical `scene_###` IDs globally\n- writes `screenplay.json`\n\n### Out of scope\n`screenplay_merger` does **not**:\n- perform semantic validation\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- polish TTS text\n\n### Output contract principle\nThe merged screenplay should preserve order while normalizing scene IDs into one canonical sequence for the rest of S1.\n\nThe supervisor must not merge unvalidated or failed batch outputs into the canonical screenplay.\n\n## Sixth implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nPlan small, stable polish batches from the merged screenplay so that `tts_polish` receives manageable groups of scenes instead of the full screenplay at once.\n\n### Scope\n- receives `screenplay.json`\n- groups scenes by count and approximate word budget\n- preserves scene order\n- emits a stable `tp_###` batch sequence\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_batch_planner` does **not**:\n- perform TTS polish\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- decide retry policy\n\n## Seventh implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `tts_polish` operator for each planned polish batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives merged screenplay\n- receives one polish batch from `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- injects `tts_polish_rules` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_io_adapter` does **not**:\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Output contract principle\nEach polish batch payload should explicitly tell `tts_polish`:\n- which scenes belong to the batch\n- what the original narration is\n- what rules govern polish behavior\n- where to write the result\n\n## Eighth implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `tts_polish` into one canonical `tts_polished.json` while preserving screenplay order and preserving the distinction between original narration and TTS-polished narration.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered polish batch files\n- validates minimum required polish scene fields\n- rebuilds one ordered `tts_polished.json`\n- uses screenplay order as the canonical scene sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_merger` does **not**:\n- validate semantic quality of the polish\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- overwrite the original screenplay artifact\n\n### Output contract principle\nThe merged polish output should preserve:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\nwithout destroying the original screenplay layer.\n\n## Ninth implemented supervisor skill: `retry_planner`\n\nThe unit of retry for `scene_director` failures should be the individual batch, not the global screenplay, unless a broader sector-level failure clearly justifies escalation.\n\n### Purpose\nTurn observed failures into explicit retry decisions so the S1 Supervisor can decide whether to abort, rerun a whole step, or rerun only affected batches.\n\n### Scope\n- classifies failure types into retry strategies\n- enforces retry limits\n- supports fail-fast structural errors\n- supports batch-subset retries for localized operator/semantic failures\n- supports step-level retries when failures are broader\n\n### Out of scope\n`retry_planner` does **not**:\n- run retries itself\n- inspect semantic payloads deeply\n- invoke operators or validators\n- write checkpoints\n\n### Decision categories in v1\n- `abort`\n- `step`\n- `batch_subset`\n\nFor `scene_director` batch validation failures, the retry planner should conceptually distinguish between:\n- structural patch candidates\n- batch repair candidates\n- full batch regeneration candidates\n\n## Tenth implemented supervisor skill: `scene_director_output_validator`\n\n### Purpose\nValidate each `scene_director` batch output independently before any merge into canonical `screenplay.json` happens.\n\n### Scope\n- validate output shape for one batch result\n- validate required scene fields\n- validate `scene_local_id` ordering/sequencing\n- validate scene span ordering and non-overlap\n- validate coverage of the intended batch source span\n- validate that `narration_original` matches the source text assigned to each scene\n- classify failures for supervisor retry handling\n\n### Out of scope\n`scene_director_output_validator` does **not**:\n- merge batches\n- decide final retry policy by itself\n- rewrite operator outputs directly\n- judge creative quality beyond deterministic structural/fidelity checks\n\n### Supervisory rule\nThe supervisor should validate each batch separately and only send approved batches into `screenplay_merger`.\n\n## Eleventh implemented supervisor skill: `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### Purpose\nProduce the final structured sector result that the S1 Supervisor can return upward after the sector finishes or fails.\n\n### Scope\n- aggregates scene counts\n- aggregates batch counts\n- exposes `scene_bible_path`\n- exposes checkpoint list\n- determines final `status` / `next_step`\n- preserves warnings/errors in one final result object\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_result_summarizer` does **not**:\n- run the sector\n- write checkpoints\n- validate semantic correctness\n- call operators or skills\n\n## Twelfth implemented supervisor skill: `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Purpose\nProvide the controlled parallelism layer for batchable operators so the supervisor can launch work in capped waves instead of all-at-once or fully sequentially.\n\n### Scope\n- receives operator batches\n- applies a concurrency cap\n- groups batches into execution waves\n- summarizes execution outcomes into completed / failed / pending sets\n\n### Initial supported operators\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n\n### Out of scope\n`operator_batch_scheduler` does **not**:\n- invoke OpenClaw operators by itself yet\n- decide semantic retry logic\n- merge outputs\n- validate content\n\n## Current status summary\nAt this stage:\n- the S1 Supervisor is defined as an OpenClaw LLM supervisor\n- deterministic helper skills are being formalized\n- `s1_preflight_checker` is implemented as the entry gate for the sector\n- `s1_paths_resolver` is implemented as the canonical path/structure resolver for the sector\n- `script_batch_planner` is implemented as the first batching/planning skill for the sector\n- `scene_director_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `scene_director` operator\n- `scene_director_output_validator` is now required as the deterministic per-batch validation gate for `scene_director` outputs before merge\n- `screenplay_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for approved batch screenplay outputs\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner` is implemented as the batching/planning layer for `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `tts_polish` operator\n- `tts_polish_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for batch polish outputs\n- `retry_planner` is implemented as the retry decision layer for the supervisor\n- `s1_result_summarizer` is implemented as the final sector result aggregation layer\n- `operator_batch_scheduler` is implemented as the controlled parallel scheduling layer for batchable operators\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978781716}}
{"type":"message","id":"5edc5fa4","parentId":"ffb3c687","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:41.963Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_y7w0WdvAbwpdoEicImuO72V9|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab26c8193853549c4151f05ea","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Scene Director Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `scene_director` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._ \n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `scene_director` is the S1 operator responsible for interpreting the script and transforming it into the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nIts job is to convert script material into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining scene boundaries and the narrative function of each scene in a way that gives the rest of the pipeline a clear structural base.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `scene_director` is:\n\n> Transform the script into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining the division and narrative function of each scene as the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nThis means `scene_director` is not just a text splitter. It is the operator that gives narrative shape to the script at the scene level.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator.\n\nIts output is the foundational scene structure that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical sector artifacts\n- used by downstream S1 steps such as polish and scene bible construction\n\n`scene_director` does not own the whole sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`scene_director` does **not** receive the entire script in one call.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `script_batch_planner` to split the raw script into manageable batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`sd_001`, `sd_002`, ...)\n- the supervisor uses `scene_director_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `scene_director` operates on one batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges batch outputs into canonical `screenplay.json`\n\nThis keeps batching, scheduling, and merge logic out of the operator itself.\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `scene_director` should receive a supervisor-prepared batch payload rather than the full script.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`sd_###`)\n- batch text\n- batch range metadata (`start_word`, `end_word`, `word_count`)\n- structural constraints relevant to scene generation\n- `scene_words_range` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to interpret the batch well, but should not be overloaded with unrelated downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`scene_director` should **not** be responsible for:\n- planning script batches\n- deciding parallelism/concurrency strategy\n- merging batch outputs globally\n- validating sector completion\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path orchestration\n- final asset planning, prompt writing, or visual execution details\n\nIt also should not collapse into a purely mechanical splitter. Its role is semantic and editorial, but still bounded.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the batch payload\n- deciding when `scene_director` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating batch outputs before merge\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n- deciding whether a failed batch should be patched, repaired, regenerated, or aborted\n\n`scene_director` is responsible for producing the batch-level scene structure output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n### Validation and correction loop\n- each `scene_director` batch output is a separately validatable unit\n- batch outputs must be validated individually before any global screenplay merge happens\n- if one batch fails validation, the supervisor should target only that batch rather than disturbing already-approved batches\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic skills, not to `scene_director`\n- `scene_director` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for the affected batch only\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nFor each batch, `scene_director` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\n- batch identity/context\n- ordered batch scenes\n- no global merge responsibility\n\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### Required scene fields\nEach scene produced by `scene_director` should contain:\n- `scene_local_id`\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `narration_original`\n\n### Structural / traceability fields\nEach scene should also contain:\n- `start_word`\n- `end_word`\n- `estimated_scene_word_count`\n\n### Span coordinate rule\nFor `scene_director` outputs, `start_word` and `end_word` should be **relative to the batch**, not absolute to the full script.\n\nThis means:\n- each batch defines its own local word coordinate system\n- the first word in the batch is word `1`\n- downstream deterministic logic may later convert or enrich spans with global coordinates if needed\n\n### Output principles\n- scenes must be ordered\n- `scene_local_id` must be sequential within the batch\n- `narration_original` must preserve the original text assigned to that scene\n- scene boundaries must not overlap\n- scene coverage must account for the full intended batch span\n- global canonical `scene_###` IDs are not the responsibility of `scene_director`; they are assigned later by deterministic merge logic\n\nThis output should be rich enough to preserve the creative and structural value of the operator, while remaining narrower than a full `scene_bible` or downstream visual planning artifact.\n\n### Correction modes\n`scene_director` should conceptually support at least two invocation modes under supervisor control:\n- `generate` -> produce a fresh batch result from the batch payload\n- `repair` -> revise one previously generated batch result using structured supervisor feedback\n\nImportant: `repair` does not mean `scene_director` self-manages validation or retry policy. The supervisor remains the owner of:\n- validation\n- retry classification\n- accept/reject decisions\n- deciding whether a problem is patchable, repairable, or requires batch regeneration\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good `scene_director` output should:\n- break the batch into scenes that make narrative sense\n- assign each scene a clear narrative function\n- preserve original narration accurately scene by scene\n- maintain clean ordering and non-overlapping boundaries\n- avoid missing or duplicating source text\n- produce a structure that can be merged deterministically and developed further by downstream S1 steps\n\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\n- overlap between scene text spans\n- missing coverage of source text\n- duplicated coverage of source text\n- non-sequential `scene_local_id`\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\n- `narration_original` drifting away from the actual source text for that scene\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `scene_director`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position as the first semantic operator inside S1\n- its batch-based execution model under supervisor control\n- the current draft of its input contract\n\nThe next step is to refine the exact repair semantics and any field-level constraints needed for implementation.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978781833}}
{"type":"message","id":"1c1de296","parentId":"5edc5fa4","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.108Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_wtZfaKNnWRTqqDH9db1DiIPq|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2748193a70afc96260a640b","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 TTS Polish Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `tts_polish` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish` operator is responsible for transforming original scene narration into a version optimized for Text-to-Speech while preserving meaning, information, coverage, and scene order.\n\nIts job is not to rewrite the story, but to apply only the minimum necessary oral/reading adjustments so the narration sounds better in synthetic voice output.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish` is:\n\n> Adjust the oral formulation of small ordered batches of scenes for TTS, preserving content, coverage, and scene order while improving pronunciation-readiness, readability, and speech naturalness.\n\nThis means `tts_polish` is a controlled oral-normalization operator, not a free narrative rewriter.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `tts_polish` operates after the canonical `screenplay.json` exists and before scene bible construction.\n\nIts output is the TTS-optimized narration layer that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical `tts_polished.json`\n- consumed by downstream audio generation and scene bible construction\n\n`tts_polish` does not own sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`tts_polish` operates on small ordered batches of scenes rather than on the full screenplay at once.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `tts_polish_batch_planner` to group scenes into manageable polish batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`tp_001`, `tp_002`, ...)\n- each batch preserves screenplay scene order\n- the supervisor uses `tts_polish_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `tts_polish` operates on one polish batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges approved batch outputs into canonical `tts_polished.json`\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `tts_polish` should receive a supervisor-prepared polish batch payload.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`tp_###`)\n- ordered batch scenes\n- for each scene: `scene_id` and `narration_original`\n- language / channel context relevant to polish behavior\n- `tts_polish_rules` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to polish the assigned scenes correctly, but should not be overloaded with unrelated upstream/downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`tts_polish` should **not** be responsible for:\n- re-structuring the narrative\n- changing scene order\n- merging or splitting scenes\n- batching logic\n- retry policy\n- semantic validation of its own output\n- visual planning\n- audio generation\n- timestamps or alignment\n\nIt also should not drift into stylistic rewriting beyond what is necessary for TTS readiness.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the polish batch payload\n- deciding when `tts_polish` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating batch outputs before merge\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n- deciding whether failures should trigger subset repair, batch regeneration, semantic review, or abort\n\n`tts_polish` is responsible for producing the batch-level TTS-polished output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n### Validation and correction loop\n- each `tts_polish` batch output is a separately validatable unit\n- semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch\n- if one subset of scenes fails, the supervisor should prefer targeted repair of affected scenes when possible\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic/semantic review layers, not to `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes in the batch\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nFor each batch, `tts_polish` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\n- batch identity/context\n- ordered batch scenes\n- no global merge responsibility\n\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### Required scene fields\nEach scene produced by `tts_polish` should contain:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\n### Optional scene fields\n- `changes`\n\n### Output principles\n- scene order must be preserved exactly\n- `scene_id` mapping must be preserved exactly\n- `narration_original` must remain the original scene narration\n- `narration_tts` may improve oral readability, but must not alter meaning or information\n- the output should preserve scene granularity and not collapse scenes together\n- global merge of polish batches is not the responsibility of `tts_polish`\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good `tts_polish` output should:\n- sound better for TTS than the original raw narration\n- preserve meaning and information fully\n- avoid eating words or adding unauthorized content\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\n- remain narrower than broad narrative rewriting\n\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\n- eaten words\n- unauthorized additions\n- meaning drift\n- scene mismatch inside batch output\n- reordered scene outputs\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `tts_polish`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position inside S1\n- its small-batch execution model\n- the current draft of its input/output contracts\n- the expected targeted-repair behavior for affected scene subsets\n\nThe next step is to formalize the output validator contract and then define the real OpenClaw workspace for the operator.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978781963}}
{"type":"message","id":"d52415a9","parentId":"1c1de296","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.228Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3fvymYszCMlMuK70rim9GWl8|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab278819386a048f80ddb1335","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# IDENTITY.md — SM-S1\n\n## Name\nSM-S1 — Supervisor do Setor de Pré-Produção\n\n## Role\nSupervisor do S1 (Pre-Production) da Content Factory.\n\n## Mission\nReceber uma run `ready_for_s1` e coordenar o setor até produzir:\n- `screenplay.json`\n- `screenplay_validation.json`\n- `tts_polished.json`\n- `polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- checkpoints `b1_*`\n\n## What I supervise\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n- validators determinísticos\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- checkpointing do setor\n- retries / fail / continue / escalate\n\n## What I do not do directly\n- não gerar screenplay eu mesmo\n- não fazer TTS polish eu mesmo\n- não validar semanticamente por conta própria quando já existe skill determinística\n- não avançar para S2/S3\n- não decidir produção global (isso pertence a camadas acima)\n\n## Operating model\nSou um supervisor LLM/OpenClaw apoiado por skills Python determinísticas e operators especializados.\n\n## Canonical references\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1_supervisor_contract.md`\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978782109}}
{"type":"message","id":"082cc833","parentId":"d52415a9","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.346Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_qXufYwvGRVSZCKncMbmuYxhb|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab280819388ebdacaceb28423","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# WORKFLOW.md — SM-S1\n\n## Canonical sector flow\n1. Run `s1_preflight_checker`\n2. Run `s1_paths_resolver`\n3. Plan script batches via `script_batch_planner`\n4. Build scene_director payloads via `scene_director_io_adapter`\n5. Schedule scene_director batches with controlled parallelism\n6. Merge scene_director outputs via `screenplay_merger`\n7. Validate screenplay\n8. If validation fails, use `retry_planner`\n9. Plan polish batches via `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n10. Build tts_polish payloads via `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n11. Schedule tts_polish batches with controlled parallelism\n12. Merge polish outputs via `tts_polish_merger`\n13. Validate polish\n14. If validation fails, use `retry_planner`\n15. Build `scene_bible.json`\n16. Validate scene bible schema\n17. Write/check checkpoints\n18. Summarize sector result via `s1_result_summarizer`\n19. Complete or fail the sector\n\n## Important workflow rules\n- Preserve persisted file contracts\n- Preserve original narration separately from TTS-polished narration\n- Use selective retry when possible\n- Do not overwrite original screenplay with polished narration\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978782228}}
{"type":"message","id":"810dced8","parentId":"082cc833","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.465Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_QVqjImVwVtxsinJshm98kCFY|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2848193b79e348eb993fbad","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# STATE.md — SM-S1\n\n## Sector state model\nThe supervisor should reason about states such as:\n- `not_started`\n- `running`\n- `retrying`\n- `blocked`\n- `complete`\n- `failed`\n\n## Retry policy (v1)\n- structural preflight failures -> fail fast\n- operator execution failures -> retry batch or step depending on mapping\n- semantic screenplay failures -> retry affected batches when possible\n- semantic polish failures -> retry affected polish batches when possible\n- scene_bible builder failures -> retry builder step\n- retry limit -> abort\n\n## Parallelism policy (initial)\n- `scene_director_concurrency_cap = 2`\n- `tts_polish_concurrency_cap = 4`\n\n## Parallelism rules\n- parallelize only batchable operators\n- keep validators, mergers, builders, and preflight sequential\n- do not launch all batches at once without a cap\n- preserve selective retry rather than rerunning everything by default\n\n## Escalation rule\nIf retries are exhausted or structural issues persist, fail clearly and escalate upward rather than improvising hidden recovery.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978782346}}
{"type":"message","id":"8978f206","parentId":"810dced8","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.587Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_nXZLsWoYS3xWMRI9Kc3meIYk|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2888193a4c6f5f958b68e20","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_scene_director`, the first semantic/creative operator inside S1 (Pre-Production).\n\nYour job is to transform one script batch into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve the original source text exactly in `narration_original`\n2. Create clean, coherent scene boundaries\n3. Give each scene a clear narrative function\n4. Keep the output structurally valid and easy to validate/merge\n5. Do not drift into downstream responsibilities\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like a narrative structurer, not like a visual planner.\n- Your task is not to decorate the batch with downstream creative ideas.\n- Your task is to shape the batch into scenes that make narrative sense and can support the rest of the pipeline.\n- Prefer clarity and fidelity over flourish.\n- Prefer clean structure over cleverness.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good result:\n- preserves all source text\n- has no overlap and no missing coverage\n- gives each scene a meaningful title\n- gives each scene a concise but useful summary\n- makes the narrative role of each scene obvious\n- stays fully inside the assigned batch\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad output includes:\n- rewritten or paraphrased narration\n- scenes with vague or generic narrative roles\n- scene boundaries that feel arbitrary\n- output that starts planning visuals, shots, prompts, or assets\n- batch-global confusion (acting as if you own the whole script)\n\n## Repair Mindset\n\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, treat it as a focused repair task for the affected batch only.\nDo not redesign unrelated parts of the output unless the correction logically requires it.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978782346}}
{"type":"message","id":"0465685c","parentId":"8978f206","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:39:42.702Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_JP5PvzIGjQ2q4wUbk6rlw8LW|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06dab2908193b94a89e813296aba","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish`, the S1 operator responsible for safe TTS-oriented oral normalization.\n\nYour job is to improve how scene narration will sound in synthetic voice output without changing what the narration says.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve meaning and information exactly\n2. Preserve scene identity and order exactly\n3. Preserve `narration_original` exactly as reference\n4. Improve pronunciation-readiness and readability for TTS only where necessary\n5. Avoid unnecessary rewriting\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like a controlled oral-normalization operator, not like a creative writer.\n- You are not here to improve the story itself.\n- You are here to make the narration safer and cleaner for voice synthesis.\n- Prefer minimal necessary change over aggressive polishing.\n- If a change is not clearly justified, do not make it.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good result:\n- keeps the same meaning\n- keeps the same scene order\n- keeps each scene tied to the same `scene_id`\n- improves readability for spoken output\n- handles things like abbreviations, units, ordinals, and oral awkwardness carefully\n- stays structurally easy to validate\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad output includes:\n- paraphrasing the narration freely\n- removing details because they sound awkward\n- adding clarifying words not present in the original\n- shifting tone or intent\n- acting as if you can rewrite scenes to sound more dramatic\n- changing multiple scenes more than necessary\n\n## Repair Mindset\n\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, repair only the affected scenes unless the instruction explicitly says otherwise.\nDo not redesign unaffected scenes.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774978782588}}
{"type":"message","id":"2e698e12","parentId":"0465685c","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:40:35.335Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim. Então eu vou parar de te devolver incerteza e te devolver **estrutura**.\n\nO que eu consigo ver agora é suficientemente forte para te ajudar a clarear. E a boa notícia é: **não ferrou tudo**. O que ferrou foi a continuidade mental da sessão; o sistema em si deixou rastros suficientes para reconstruirmos a lógica.\n\n## O quadro real do S1 hoje\n\nO S1 que vocês estavam construindo já tem uma forma bastante clara:\n\n### 1. A arquitectura-alvo do S1 está definida\nEla é esta:\n\n- **SM-S1** = cérebro / orquestração\n- **operators OpenClaw** = especialistas semânticos\n  - `op_s1_scene_director`\n  - `op_s1_tts_polish`\n  - `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n- **skills Python determinísticas** = mecânica, validação, merge, batching, retry, checkpoints\n- **artefactos persistidos** = verdade operacional da run\n\nIsto está muito explícito no contrato do supervisor:\n- *Supervisor = brain*\n- *Skills = hands*\n- *Operators = specialists*\n\nOu seja: a visão já estava certa. Não é um S1 improvisado.\n\n---\n\n## O fluxo canónico do S1 está praticamente desenhado\n\nO workflow do supervisor está assim:\n\n1. `s1_preflight_checker`\n2. `s1_paths_resolver`\n3. `script_batch_planner`\n4. `scene_director_io_adapter`\n5. scheduler com paralelismo controlado\n6. `screenplay_merger`\n7. validação do screenplay\n8. `retry_planner`\n9. `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n10. `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n11. scheduler do polish\n12. `tts_polish_merger`\n13. validação do polish\n14. `retry_planner`\n15. `scene_bible_builder`\n16. schema validation\n17. checkpoints\n18. `s1_result_summarizer`\n19. finish/fail\n\nIsto não é pouca coisa. Isto já é um desenho operacional bem maduro.\n\n---\n\n## Então qual é a confusão real?\n\nA confusão real não é “o que é o S1?”.  \nA confusão real é:\n\n> **o quanto desse desenho já está realmente “plumbed together” de forma canónica, e o quanto ainda está parcialmente concentrado no `runtime/s1/s1_start.py`**\n\nPorque hoje coexistem duas camadas:\n\n### Camada A — arquitectura canónica\n- contratos S1\n- workspaces OpenClaw dos agentes\n- operadores especializados\n- skills supervisoras explícitas\n- batching / merge / retry / scheduler / summarizer\n\n### Camada B — implementação de execução actual\n- `runtime/s1/s1_start.py`\n- `scene_director_runner.py`\n- `tts_polish_runner.py`\n- validators/builders/checkpoint writer\n\nE o teu sentimento de “faltavam nuances importantes” bate exactamente com isso.\n\n---\n\n# A clareza que eu te devolvo agora\n\n## O que já está claro e parece decidido\n\n### A. Naming canónico do sector\n- **`b1_` é o naming canónico**\n- não `s1_`\n\nIsso está consistente nos contratos e no runtime actual.\n\n### B. Outputs canónicos do S1\nO supervisor deve terminar com:\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- checkpoints `b1_*`\n\nIsto está cristalino.\n\n### C. Papel de cada peça principal\n- **SM-S1** coordena\n- **scene_director** transforma batch de script em cenas\n- **tts_polish** transforma cenas em narração TTS-safe\n- **validators/mergers/builders** ficam fora dos operators\n- **scene_bible** é o artefacto final do S1\n\n### D. O scene_director já está muito bem conceptualizado\nO contrato dele está sólido:\n- recebe **um batch**\n- não o script inteiro\n- não faz batching\n- não faz merge\n- não faz visual planning downstream\n- devolve cenas com:\n  - `scene_local_id`\n  - `scene_title`\n  - `scene_summary`\n  - `narrative_function`\n  - `narration_original`\n  - `start_word`\n  - `end_word`\n  - `estimated_scene_word_count`\n\nIsto é muito bom. Aqui há bastante maturidade.\n\n### E. O tts_polish também já está bem conceptualizado\nO contrato dele também está claro:\n- opera em batches pequenos de cenas\n- preserva `scene_id`\n- preserva `narration_original`\n- devolve `narration_tts`\n- não reestrutura narrativa\n- não muda ordem\n- não faz merge nem retry policy\n\nTambém aqui há bastante clareza.\n\n---\n\n# Onde está a névoa real\n\nAgora a parte importante: onde é que ainda falta fechar.\n\n## 1. O supervisor canónico ainda parece mais avançado no contrato do que na execução real\nO contrato do supervisor lista como “implemented now” várias skills:\n\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\nMas no snapshot que eu vi em `runtime/s1`, os ficheiros visíveis eram outros:\n- `s1_start.py`\n- `scene_director_runner.py`\n- `tts_polish_runner.py`\n- validators/builders/checkpoint writer\n\nEntão, a primeira clareza é esta:\n\n> **Ou estas skills já existem noutro sítio e eu ainda não as li, ou o contrato está à frente da implementação consolidada.**\n\nIsto é importante porque muda o diagnóstico:\n- se as skills já existem → problema é integração/alinhamento\n- se não existem ainda → problema é que parte do workflow ainda está “colapsada” em runners/entrypoint\n\n---\n\n## 2. O `s1_start.py` ainda parece representar uma versão mais simples que o workflow canónico\nO `s1_start.py` actual faz isto:\n\n- lê config\n- lê script\n- chama `run_scene_director`\n- valida screenplay\n- chama `run_tts_polish`\n- valida polish\n- constrói scene bible\n- escreve checkpoints\n\nOu seja:\n- **não há batch scheduler explícito**\n- **não há io adapters explícitos**\n- **não há mergers explícitos no entrypoint**\n- **não há selective retry por subset/batch de forma rica**\n- **não há passagem explícita pelos operators OpenClaw**\n\nEntão a tua sensação de que ainda faltavam nuances de:\n- lógica do workflow\n- relações dos operators com supervisor\n- supervisor com skills\n\n…está totalmente alinhada com o que eu estou a ver.\n\n---\n\n## 3. O maior ponto estrutural que falta clarear é a autoridade operacional\nEsta é a pergunta-mãe do S1 neste momento:\n\n### Quem é o runtime real do S1?\n\nHá 3 possibilidades:\n\n#### Opção 1 — `s1_start.py` continua a ser o runtime canónico\nNesse caso:\n- os agents OpenClaw servem como especificação/prompts invocáveis\n- mas o verdadeiro orquestrador continua Python\n- e o próximo passo é adaptar `s1_start.py` para usar as skills e operators certos\n\n#### Opção 2 — `sm_s1_pre_production` deve virar o runtime canónico\nNesse caso:\n- o `s1_start.py` vira bootstrap/transição\n- o supervisor OpenClaw passa a comandar de verdade\n- skills Python ficam como ferramentas chamadas por ele\n\n#### Opção 3 — modelo híbrido\n- Python continua como entrypoint\n- mas passa a delegar semanticamente para agents OpenClaw\n- e delega mecanicamente para skills Python separadas\n- ficando como uma espécie de thin runtime shell\n\n**A minha recomendação, olhando o estado actual, é a Opção 3 como transição canónica.**\n\nPorquê?\nPorque:\n- já existe runtime Python funcional\n- já existem agents/contracts OpenClaw maduros\n- tentar matar o Python bootstrap cedo demais pode criar mais caos do que clareza\n- mas manter tudo concentrado no `s1_start.py` também mata a arquitectura\n\nEntão o melhor caminho parece ser:\n> **manter `s1_start.py` como entrypoint transitório, mas obrigá-lo a operar pelas contracts/skills/operators canónicos, e não por lógica colapsada**\n\n---\n\n# O que eu acho que faltava destrinchar na sessão\n\nBaseado em tudo isto, eu diria que as nuances que vocês estavam mais perto de precisar fechar eram estas:\n\n## 1. Contrato operacional do SM-S1\nNão a missão abstracta — isso já está bem.\nMas sim:\n- que skill ele chama primeiro\n- com que input exacto\n- o que ele espera de output\n- quando ele chama operator vs skill\n- quando escreve checkpoint\n- quando faz retry de batch vs retry de step\n\n## 2. Contrato real do `scene_director`\nO contrato conceitual está bom.\nO que provavelmente faltava era:\n- payload exacto de input\n- output file exacto\n- repair mode exacto\n- quem valida o quê\n- se o output já inclui campos suficientes para o merger/builders downstream sem remendos\n\n## 3. Contrato real do `tts_polish`\nMesma coisa:\n- batch payload exacto\n- output file exacto\n- relação com semantic reviewer\n- em que momento o reviewer entra\n- se reviewer é sempre chamado ou só borderline\n- como o supervisor decide subset retry\n\n## 4. Fronteira entre validators determinísticos e reviewer semântico\nTu tens:\n- `polish_validator`\n- `s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract`\n- `s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract`\n- agent `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\nIsto é uma pista fortíssima de que uma nuance central provavelmente era:\n\n> **quando a validação determinística basta, e quando entra o reviewer semântico?**\n\nIsto é muito importante porque sem essa regra o fluxo fica ambíguo.\n\n---\n\n# A minha leitura prática do estado do S1\n\nSe eu tivesse de te devolver o estado em linguagem simples:\n\n### O S1 já tem 80%+ da espinha dorsal conceptual pronta.\nO que falta não é inventar o S1.\n\nO que falta é **fechar o encaixe operacional** entre:\n- supervisor\n- operators\n- skills\n- entrypoint Python\n- artefactos\n\nOu ainda mais simples:\n\n> **o sistema já sabe o que quer ser; falta garantir que executa exactamente desse jeito**\n\n---\n\n# O que eu te recomendo fazer agora, sem depender da tua memória\n\nEu consigo liderar isto contigo sem tu me responder essas perguntas no escuro.\n\n## Próximo movimento mais inteligente\nEu sugiro esta sequência:\n\n### Passo 1 — eu faço um “mapa de autoridade” do S1\nUm documento curto respondendo:\n- quem decide\n- quem gera\n- quem valida\n- quem faz merge\n- quem escreve\n- quem retria\n- quem faz escalate\n\n### Passo 2 — eu faço um “gap map” entre:\n- contratos/workspaces OpenClaw\n- runtime Python actual\n\n### Passo 3 — disso sai uma lista clara de:\n- o que já está consistente\n- o que ainda está duplicado\n- o que está implícito\n- o que falta formalizar\n\nIsto vai te devolver contexto operacional sem depender da tua lembrança da sessão perdida.\n\n---\n\n# Recomendação objectiva\nSe eu tivesse de resumir em uma frase:\n\n> **o S1 não está perdido; ele está num ponto avançado mas com autoridade e integração ainda parcialmente difusas, e o trabalho agora é clarificar essa topologia antes de continuar a empilhar implementação**\n\nSe quiser, eu começo já pelo **Passo 1: mapa de autoridade do S1 actual**.  \nEsse é o melhor jeito de te devolver chão firme rapidamente.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06e1404481939322c9de1570f174\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":8426,"output":2641,"cacheRead":116736,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":127803,"cost":{"input":0.021065,"output":0.039615000000000004,"cacheRead":0.029183999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.089864}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774978783546,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc06e056488193aa73b5f6c7fe2cd1"}}
