{"type":"message","id":"e75a065a","parentId":"bf5bfb65","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:58:48.732Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_4jOQaF0cURgFDfKaeh3qnOzX|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b4511fc8193ac40b59feec2229e","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_tts_polish_merger_contract.md","content":"# S1 TTS Polish Merger Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic merge contract that produces canonical `tts_polished.json` from approved polish batch outputs._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish_merger` merges batch outputs from `tts_polish` into one canonical `tts_polished.json` while preserving screenplay order and preserving the distinction between original narration and TTS-polished narration.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nThis component sits after:\n- `tts_polish`\n- any optional semantic review lane applied under supervisor control\n\nAnd before:\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- downstream sectors that depend on TTS narration readiness\n\n---\n\n## Ownership\n\n### Owned by\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\n\n### Not owned by\n- `tts_polish`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe merger should receive:\n- ordered polish batch output files\n- canonical `screenplay`\n- optional canonical `output_path`\n\n### Critical precondition\nThe merger should only receive batch outputs that the supervisor has accepted for merge.\nRejected, incomplete, or stale outputs should not be treated as canonical polish truth.\n\n---\n\n## Responsibilities\n\nThe merger should:\n- load ordered polish batch output files\n- validate minimum required polish fields for merge compatibility\n- rebuild one ordered `tts_polished.json` using screenplay order as the source of truth\n- preserve `scene_id`\n- preserve `narration_original`\n- preserve `narration_tts`\n- write canonical `tts_polished.json`\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\nThe merger must **not**:\n- perform semantic quality validation\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- overwrite the canonical screenplay artifact\n- invent polish for missing scenes\n- rewrite scene identities\n\n---\n\n## Required input assumptions\n\nEach accepted polish batch file should contain scene entries with at minimum:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\nOptional:\n- `changes`\n\nThe screenplay must provide the canonical scene ordering reference.\n\n---\n\n## Canonical output structure\n\nThe merger should produce:\n```json\n{\n  \"scene_count\": 24,\n  \"scenes\": [\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_001\",\n      \"narration_original\": \"...\",\n      \"narration_tts\": \"...\",\n      \"changes\": [\"...\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Merge principles\n\n### Ordering\n- screenplay order is canonical\n- polish outputs must be reassembled according to screenplay order, not arrival order\n\n### Identity preservation\n- `scene_id` must be preserved exactly\n- original scene identity must not be rewritten here\n\n### Original vs polished narration\n- `narration_original` must remain preserved\n- `narration_tts` must remain a separate layer\n- the merger must not collapse the distinction between screenplay narration and TTS narration\n\n### Missing outputs\nIf a screenplay scene has no corresponding accepted polish output, that is an error.\nThe merger must not invent content to fill the gap.\n\n---\n\n## Error policy\n\nThe merger should fail clearly when merge prerequisites are not met.\n\nExamples:\n- no polish batch files provided\n- missing batch file\n- invalid batch JSON\n- invalid batch scenes payload\n- missing required polish fields\n- missing polish output for a screenplay scene\n\nWarnings may be emitted for soft anomalies such as:\n- duplicate scene polish across batches, where latest value is currently kept\n\n---\n\n## Output path expectation\n\nThe canonical merged artifact should normally be written to:\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n\nThe merger may also return the in-memory merged structure to the supervisor.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with downstream validation\n\nThe merger is not the final polish-quality gate.\nAfter merge, the supervisor should pass the resulting canonical polish artifact to:\n- `polish_validator`\n\nThis separation is important:\n- operator output / optional semantic review = upstream generation/review layers\n- `tts_polish_merger` = deterministic composition layer\n- `polish_validator` = whole-polish validation layer\n\n---\n\n## Current implementation note\n\nThe current implementation lives in:\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/tts_polish_merger.py`\n\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_tts_polish_merger_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 TTS Polish Merger Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic merge contract that produces canonical `tts_polished.json` from approved polish batch outputs._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `tts_polish_merger` merges batch outputs from `tts_polish` into one canonical `tts_polished.json` while preserving screenplay order and preserving the distinction between original narration and TTS-polished narration.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nThis component sits after:\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- any optional semantic review lane applied under supervisor control\\n\\nAnd before:\\n- `polish_validator`\\n- `scene_bible_builder`\\n- downstream sectors that depend on TTS narration readiness\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ownership\\n\\n### Owned by\\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\\n\\n### Not owned by\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- `polish_validator`\\n- `scene_bible_builder`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\nThe merger should receive:\\n- ordered polish batch output files\\n- canonical `screenplay`\\n- optional canonical `output_path`\\n\\n### Critical precondition\\nThe merger should only receive batch outputs that the supervisor has accepted for merge.\\nRejected, incomplete, or stale outputs should not be treated as canonical polish truth.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Responsibilities\\n\\nThe merger should:\\n- load ordered polish batch output files\\n- validate minimum required polish fields for merge compatibility\\n- rebuild one ordered `tts_polished.json` using screenplay order as the source of truth\\n- preserve `scene_id`\\n- preserve `narration_original`\\n- preserve `narration_tts`\\n- write canonical `tts_polished.json`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\nThe merger must **not**:\\n- perform semantic quality validation\\n- decide retry policy\\n- invoke operators\\n- overwrite the canonical screenplay artifact\\n- invent polish for missing scenes\\n- rewrite scene identities\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Required input assumptions\\n\\nEach accepted polish batch file should contain scene entries with at minimum:\\n- `scene_id`\\n- `narration_original`\\n- `narration_tts`\\n\\nOptional:\\n- `changes`\\n\\nThe screenplay must provide the canonical scene ordering reference.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical output structure\\n\\nThe merger should produce:\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"scene_count\\\": 24,\\n  \\\"scenes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_001\\\",\\n      \\\"narration_original\\\": \\\"...\\\",\\n      \\\"narration_tts\\\": \\\"...\\\",\\n      \\\"changes\\\": [\\\"...\\\"]\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Merge principles\\n\\n### Ordering\\n- screenplay order is canonical\\n- polish outputs must be reassembled according to screenplay order, not arrival order\\n\\n### Identity preservation\\n- `scene_id` must be preserved exactly\\n- original scene identity must not be rewritten here\\n\\n### Original vs polished narration\\n- `narration_original` must remain preserved\\n- `narration_tts` must remain a separate layer\\n- the merger must not collapse the distinction between screenplay narration and TTS narration\\n\\n### Missing outputs\\nIf a screenplay scene has no corresponding accepted polish output, that is an error.\\nThe merger must not invent content to fill the gap.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Error policy\\n\\nThe merger should fail clearly when merge prerequisites are not met.\\n\\nExamples:\\n- no polish batch files provided\\n- missing batch file\\n- invalid batch JSON\\n- invalid batch scenes payload\\n- missing required polish fields\\n- missing polish output for a screenplay scene\\n\\nWarnings may be emitted for soft anomalies such as:\\n- duplicate scene polish across batches, where latest value is currently kept\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output path expectation\\n\\nThe canonical merged artifact should normally be written to:\\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\\n\\nThe merger may also return the in-memory merged structure to the supervisor.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship with downstream validation\\n\\nThe merger is not the final polish-quality gate.\\nAfter merge, the supervisor should pass the resulting canonical polish artifact to:\\n- `polish_validator`\\n\\nThis separation is important:\\n- operator output / optional semantic review = upstream generation/review layers\\n- `tts_polish_merger` = deterministic composition layer\\n- `polish_validator` = whole-polish validation layer\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current implementation note\\n\\nThe current implementation lives in:\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/tts_polish_merger.py`\\n\\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":177,"output":1089,"cacheRead":115328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":116594,"cost":{"input":0.0004425,"output":0.016335,"cacheRead":0.028832,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0456095}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774979904969,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b4215e881938d8133d99eae50ac"}}
{"type":"message","id":"97ad21e1","parentId":"e75a065a","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:58:49.309Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_4jOQaF0cURgFDfKaeh3qnOzX|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b4511fc8193ac40b59feec2229e","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 4233 bytes to C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_tts_polish_merger_contract.md"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774979929186}}
{"type":"message","id":"2829b71e","parentId":"97ad21e1","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:59:11.453Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_HDD6b05uRUUCxYGLlH63GYKp|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b5c02688193a113ad3cb8d59aae","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_retry_planner_contract.md","content":"# S1 Retry Planner Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic retry-policy helper used by the S1 Supervisor._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `retry_planner` turns observed failures into explicit retry recommendations so the S1 Supervisor can decide whether to:\n- abort\n- rerun a full step\n- rerun only affected batches/subsets\n\nIt is a policy helper, not a sector owner.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nThis component sits wherever the supervisor needs structured retry guidance after:\n- operator execution failures\n- batch validation failures\n- merge failures\n- screenplay validation failures\n- polish validation failures\n- builder/schema failures\n- infrastructure failures\n\n---\n\n## Ownership\n\n### Owned by\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\n\n### Not owned by\n- operators\n- validators\n- builders\n- `s1_start.py` as canonical brain\n\nThe planner recommends.\nThe supervisor decides.\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe retry planner should receive, at minimum:\n- `step_name`\n- `failure_type`\n- `retry_count`\n\nOptional but important:\n- `affected_batches`\n- `affected_scenes`\n- `max_retries`\n\n---\n\n## Responsibilities\n\nThe planner should:\n- classify failure types into retry strategies\n- enforce retry limits\n- support fail-fast structural cases\n- support batch-subset retries when failures are localized\n- support step-level retries when failures are broader\n- return a deterministic recommendation object\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\nThe planner must **not**:\n- run retries itself\n- invoke operators\n- invoke validators\n- mutate artifacts\n- overwrite supervisor authority\n- act as semantic judge of operator outputs beyond provided failure typing\n\n---\n\n## Decision space\n\nCurrent recommendation space:\n- `abort`\n- `step`\n- `batch_subset`\n\n### Meaning\n- `abort` -> stop retrying and fail/escalate\n- `step` -> rerun the relevant step in a controlled way\n- `batch_subset` -> rerun only affected batches/subsets\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nThe planner should return at minimum:\n```json\n{\n  \"retry\": true,\n  \"retry_mode\": \"batch_subset\",\n  \"targets\": [\"sd_003\"],\n  \"reason\": \"Operator execution failure 'operator_timeout' — rerun affected batches\",\n  \"next_action\": \"rerun_scene_director_batches\"\n}\n```\n\n### Required fields\n- `retry`\n- `retry_mode`\n- `targets`\n- `reason`\n- `next_action`\n\n---\n\n## Policy principles\n\n### Supervisor sovereignty\nThe supervisor remains the owner of retry/fail/continue/escalate decisions.\nThe retry planner provides structured policy guidance, not sovereign control.\n\n### Prefer selective retry when safe\nIf the failure is localized and already-approved outputs can be preserved safely, the planner should prefer subset retry over global rerun.\n\n### Prefer fail-fast for structural problems\nIf the failure is structural or invalidates sector entry assumptions, the planner should recommend abort rather than improvised recovery.\n\n### Respect retry ceilings\nIf retry limits are exhausted, the planner should recommend abort.\n\n---\n\n## Current policy families in implementation\n\n### Fail-fast structural failures\nExamples:\n- missing required input\n- invalid pipeline state\n- empty script\n- `b1_already_complete`\n\n### Operator-retryable failures\nExamples:\n- timeout\n- missing output\n- invalid JSON\n- malformed output\n\n### Merge-recovery failures\nExamples:\n- missing batch file\n- invalid batch JSON\n- missing merge fields\n\n### Semantic screenplay failures\nExamples:\n- coverage failures\n- missing words\n- duplicate scene content\n\n### Semantic polish failures\nExamples:\n- eaten words\n- meaning drift\n- unauthorized additions\n\n### Builder/schema failures\nExamples:\n- scene bible build failure\n- schema invalid\n\n### Infrastructure failures\nExamples:\n- filesystem write error\n- permission error\n- disk full\n\n---\n\n## Known limitation in current v1\n\nThe current planner is primarily keyed by `failure_type` and does not yet reason deeply over rich contextual evidence.\nThat is acceptable in v1, but the supervisor should remain aware that this is a policy mapper, not a full recovery engine.\n\n---\n\n## Current implementation note\n\nThe current implementation lives in:\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/retry_planner.py`\n\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_retry_planner_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 Retry Planner Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic retry-policy helper used by the S1 Supervisor._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `retry_planner` turns observed failures into explicit retry recommendations so the S1 Supervisor can decide whether to:\\n- abort\\n- rerun a full step\\n- rerun only affected batches/subsets\\n\\nIt is a policy helper, not a sector owner.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nThis component sits wherever the supervisor needs structured retry guidance after:\\n- operator execution failures\\n- batch validation failures\\n- merge failures\\n- screenplay validation failures\\n- polish validation failures\\n- builder/schema failures\\n- infrastructure failures\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ownership\\n\\n### Owned by\\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\\n\\n### Not owned by\\n- operators\\n- validators\\n- builders\\n- `s1_start.py` as canonical brain\\n\\nThe planner recommends.\\nThe supervisor decides.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\nThe retry planner should receive, at minimum:\\n- `step_name`\\n- `failure_type`\\n- `retry_count`\\n\\nOptional but important:\\n- `affected_batches`\\n- `affected_scenes`\\n- `max_retries`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Responsibilities\\n\\nThe planner should:\\n- classify failure types into retry strategies\\n- enforce retry limits\\n- support fail-fast structural cases\\n- support batch-subset retries when failures are localized\\n- support step-level retries when failures are broader\\n- return a deterministic recommendation object\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\nThe planner must **not**:\\n- run retries itself\\n- invoke operators\\n- invoke validators\\n- mutate artifacts\\n- overwrite supervisor authority\\n- act as semantic judge of operator outputs beyond provided failure typing\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Decision space\\n\\nCurrent recommendation space:\\n- `abort`\\n- `step`\\n- `batch_subset`\\n\\n### Meaning\\n- `abort` -> stop retrying and fail/escalate\\n- `step` -> rerun the relevant step in a controlled way\\n- `batch_subset` -> rerun only affected batches/subsets\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nThe planner should return at minimum:\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"retry\\\": true,\\n  \\\"retry_mode\\\": \\\"batch_subset\\\",\\n  \\\"targets\\\": [\\\"sd_003\\\"],\\n  \\\"reason\\\": \\\"Operator execution failure 'operator_timeout' — rerun affected batches\\\",\\n  \\\"next_action\\\": \\\"rerun_scene_director_batches\\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Required fields\\n- `retry`\\n- `retry_mode`\\n- `targets`\\n- `reason`\\n- `next_action`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Policy principles\\n\\n### Supervisor sovereignty\\nThe supervisor remains the owner of retry/fail/continue/escalate decisions.\\nThe retry planner provides structured policy guidance, not sovereign control.\\n\\n### Prefer selective retry when safe\\nIf the failure is localized and already-approved outputs can be preserved safely, the planner should prefer subset retry over global rerun.\\n\\n### Prefer fail-fast for structural problems\\nIf the failure is structural or invalidates sector entry assumptions, the planner should recommend abort rather than improvised recovery.\\n\\n### Respect retry ceilings\\nIf retry limits are exhausted, the planner should recommend abort.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current policy families in implementation\\n\\n### Fail-fast structural failures\\nExamples:\\n- missing required input\\n- invalid pipeline state\\n- empty script\\n- `b1_already_complete`\\n\\n### Operator-retryable failures\\nExamples:\\n- timeout\\n- missing output\\n- invalid JSON\\n- malformed output\\n\\n### Merge-recovery failures\\nExamples:\\n- missing batch file\\n- invalid batch JSON\\n- missing merge fields\\n\\n### Semantic screenplay failures\\nExamples:\\n- coverage failures\\n- missing words\\n- duplicate scene content\\n\\n### Semantic polish failures\\nExamples:\\n- eaten words\\n- meaning drift\\n- unauthorized additions\\n\\n### Builder/schema failures\\nExamples:\\n- scene bible build failure\\n- schema invalid\\n\\n### Infrastructure failures\\nExamples:\\n- filesystem write error\\n- permission error\\n- disk full\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Known limitation in current v1\\n\\nThe current planner is primarily keyed by `failure_type` and does not yet reason deeply over rich contextual evidence.\\nThat is acceptable in v1, but the supervisor should remain aware that this is a policy mapper, not a full recovery engine.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current implementation note\\n\\nThe current implementation lives in:\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/retry_planner.py`\\n\\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":163,"output":1077,"cacheRead":116480,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117720,"cost":{"input":0.00040750000000000004,"output":0.016155,"cacheRead":0.02912,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0456825}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774979930005,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b5aac508193976c757d3e07bbf9"}}
{"type":"message","id":"dc377861","parentId":"2829b71e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:59:12.061Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_HDD6b05uRUUCxYGLlH63GYKp|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b5c02688193a113ad3cb8d59aae","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 4224 bytes to C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_retry_planner_contract.md"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774979951925}}
{"type":"message","id":"112912d6","parentId":"dc377861","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:59:36.657Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_KmYkUFfceWwSObwQvlzij6tF|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b7488e08193b7b72877f9b8ecb2","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_operator_batch_scheduler_contract.md","content":"# S1 Operator Batch Scheduler Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic scheduling helper used by the S1 Supervisor for batchable operators._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `operator_batch_scheduler` provides the controlled parallelism layer used by the S1 Supervisor for batchable operators.\n\nIts role is to:\n- apply concurrency caps\n- group queued batches into execution waves\n- normalize execution-result summaries\n\nIt is a scheduling helper, not an operator invoker and not a sector brain.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nThis component sits between:\n- batch payload preparation\n- actual operator invocation under supervisor control\n- execution result summarization\n\nIt supports the supervisor in controlling parallelism for:\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n\n---\n\n## Ownership\n\n### Owned by\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\n\n### Not owned by\n- operators\n- retry planner\n- mergers\n- validators\n\nThe scheduler plans and summarizes.\nThe supervisor still owns the real invocation/control loop.\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\n### For wave planning\nThe scheduler should receive:\n- `operator_name`\n- `batches`\n- `concurrency_cap`\n\nEach batch should provide, at minimum:\n- `batch_id`\n- `input_path`\n- `output_path`\n- optional `status`\n\n### For execution summary\nThe scheduler should receive:\n- `operator_name`\n- `concurrency_cap`\n- `execution_results`\n\nEach execution result may provide:\n- `batch_id`\n- `status`\n- `output_path`\n- `errors`\n- `warnings`\n\n---\n\n## Responsibilities\n\nThe scheduler should:\n- validate `concurrency_cap`\n- normalize batch records for scheduling\n- group batches into execution waves/windows\n- preserve batch ordering\n- summarize completed / failed / pending batches after execution\n- expose output files from completed batches\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\nThe scheduler must **not**:\n- invoke OpenClaw operators by itself\n- decide retry policy\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge outputs\n- alter supervisor authority\n\n---\n\n## Wave planning contract\n\n### Example output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"operator\": \"scene_director\",\n  \"concurrency_cap\": 2,\n  \"total_batches\": 5,\n  \"wave_count\": 3,\n  \"waves\": [\n    {\n      \"wave_index\": 1,\n      \"batch_ids\": [\"sd_001\", \"sd_002\"],\n      \"batch_count\": 2,\n      \"batches\": [\n        {\n          \"batch_id\": \"sd_001\",\n          \"input_path\": \"...\",\n          \"output_path\": \"...\",\n          \"status\": \"queued\"\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n### Scheduling principles\n- preserve batch order\n- apply concurrency cap deterministically\n- avoid all-at-once launch\n- allow the supervisor to execute wave by wave\n\n---\n\n## Execution summary contract\n\n### Example output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": false,\n  \"operator\": \"tts_polish\",\n  \"concurrency_cap\": 4,\n  \"total_batches\": 5,\n  \"completed_batches\": [\"tp_001\", \"tp_002\"],\n  \"failed_batches\": [\"tp_003\"],\n  \"pending_batches\": [\"tp_004\", \"tp_005\"],\n  \"output_files\": [\"...\"],\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n### Summary principles\n- success is determined by whether failures occurred in the provided execution set\n- completed output files should be exposed to the supervisor\n- failed and pending sets should remain explicit for retry/control decisions\n\n---\n\n## Current limitation\n\nThis component does **not** itself perform the actual operator invocation.\nThat control loop remains a supervisor responsibility.\n\nThis is intentional.\nThe scheduler defines scheduling semantics, not sovereign execution control.\n\n---\n\n## Error policy\n\nThe scheduler should fail clearly when basic scheduling prerequisites are invalid.\n\nExamples:\n- `concurrency_cap < 1`\n- malformed batch structures severe enough to break scheduling assumptions\n\n---\n\n## Current implementation note\n\nThe current implementation lives in:\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/operator_batch_scheduler.py`\n\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_operator_batch_scheduler_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 Operator Batch Scheduler Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic scheduling helper used by the S1 Supervisor for batchable operators._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `operator_batch_scheduler` provides the controlled parallelism layer used by the S1 Supervisor for batchable operators.\\n\\nIts role is to:\\n- apply concurrency caps\\n- group queued batches into execution waves\\n- normalize execution-result summaries\\n\\nIt is a scheduling helper, not an operator invoker and not a sector brain.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nThis component sits between:\\n- batch payload preparation\\n- actual operator invocation under supervisor control\\n- execution result summarization\\n\\nIt supports the supervisor in controlling parallelism for:\\n- `scene_director`\\n- `tts_polish`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ownership\\n\\n### Owned by\\n- S1 Supervisor as a deterministic supervisor skill\\n\\n### Not owned by\\n- operators\\n- retry planner\\n- mergers\\n- validators\\n\\nThe scheduler plans and summarizes.\\nThe supervisor still owns the real invocation/control loop.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\n### For wave planning\\nThe scheduler should receive:\\n- `operator_name`\\n- `batches`\\n- `concurrency_cap`\\n\\nEach batch should provide, at minimum:\\n- `batch_id`\\n- `input_path`\\n- `output_path`\\n- optional `status`\\n\\n### For execution summary\\nThe scheduler should receive:\\n- `operator_name`\\n- `concurrency_cap`\\n- `execution_results`\\n\\nEach execution result may provide:\\n- `batch_id`\\n- `status`\\n- `output_path`\\n- `errors`\\n- `warnings`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Responsibilities\\n\\nThe scheduler should:\\n- validate `concurrency_cap`\\n- normalize batch records for scheduling\\n- group batches into execution waves/windows\\n- preserve batch ordering\\n- summarize completed / failed / pending batches after execution\\n- expose output files from completed batches\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\nThe scheduler must **not**:\\n- invoke OpenClaw operators by itself\\n- decide retry policy\\n- validate semantic quality\\n- merge outputs\\n- alter supervisor authority\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Wave planning contract\\n\\n### Example output shape\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"ok\\\": true,\\n  \\\"operator\\\": \\\"scene_director\\\",\\n  \\\"concurrency_cap\\\": 2,\\n  \\\"total_batches\\\": 5,\\n  \\\"wave_count\\\": 3,\\n  \\\"waves\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"wave_index\\\": 1,\\n      \\\"batch_ids\\\": [\\\"sd_001\\\", \\\"sd_002\\\"],\\n      \\\"batch_count\\\": 2,\\n      \\\"batches\\\": [\\n        {\\n          \\\"batch_id\\\": \\\"sd_001\\\",\\n          \\\"input_path\\\": \\\"...\\\",\\n          \\\"output_path\\\": \\\"...\\\",\\n          \\\"status\\\": \\\"queued\\\"\\n        }\\n      ]\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \\\"errors\\\": [],\\n  \\\"warnings\\\": []\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Scheduling principles\\n- preserve batch order\\n- apply concurrency cap deterministically\\n- avoid all-at-once launch\\n- allow the supervisor to execute wave by wave\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Execution summary contract\\n\\n### Example output shape\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"ok\\\": false,\\n  \\\"operator\\\": \\\"tts_polish\\\",\\n  \\\"concurrency_cap\\\": 4,\\n  \\\"total_batches\\\": 5,\\n  \\\"completed_batches\\\": [\\\"tp_001\\\", \\\"tp_002\\\"],\\n  \\\"failed_batches\\\": [\\\"tp_003\\\"],\\n  \\\"pending_batches\\\": [\\\"tp_004\\\", \\\"tp_005\\\"],\\n  \\\"output_files\\\": [\\\"...\\\"],\\n  \\\"errors\\\": [],\\n  \\\"warnings\\\": []\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Summary principles\\n- success is determined by whether failures occurred in the provided execution set\\n- completed output files should be exposed to the supervisor\\n- failed and pending sets should remain explicit for retry/control decisions\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current limitation\\n\\nThis component does **not** itself perform the actual operator invocation.\\nThat control loop remains a supervisor responsibility.\\n\\nThis is intentional.\\nThe scheduler defines scheduling semantics, not sovereign execution control.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Error policy\\n\\nThe scheduler should fail clearly when basic scheduling prerequisites are invalid.\\n\\nExamples:\\n- `concurrency_cap < 1`\\n- malformed batch structures severe enough to break scheduling assumptions\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current implementation note\\n\\nThe current implementation lives in:\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/operator_batch_scheduler.py`\\n\\nThis contract is the canonical behavioral layer for that implementation.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":134,"output":1104,"cacheRead":117632,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118870,"cost":{"input":0.000335,"output":0.016560000000000002,"cacheRead":0.029408,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.046303}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774979952847,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0b71979481938b017909993b73a2"}}
