{"type":"message","id":"5ae6f260","parentId":"c3ba5c6d","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:27.204Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vou fechar agora o lane de review/validação do polish e checar o alinhamento dos operators restantes.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c682dd88193ab3a2e4f6ecfeb9a\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_YedjodyIKxlnvnFACtZfTB9a|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e2c819397fb97714d2b6b35","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_MY2jfyx5pLpGsfMyN4lhU3Nd|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e40819389ef0d5862e2f0d4","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_evEJmo7q3BmbyTxwv7eHrm0m|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e4881939dd9862cd4584ec1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\IDENTITY.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish\\\\IDENTITY.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_G0241kmmdo4MlWwhqi4RUJ63|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e508193be118a1c4aa35a7d","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\PROMPT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish\\\\PROMPT.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_WifxIKjJLGd2SzifUlRQkriS|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e5881938ef3967499702d39","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\RULES.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish\\\\RULES.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_SihZM4mOkLEET9x95lblFtVS|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e608193b38782574788d4cb","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\IDENTITY.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\\\IDENTITY.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0cbJ022VJDNDxnqkLy7xdl1r|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e688193b191be3c96c5ec94","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\PROMPT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\\\PROMPT.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_VO5ZyumE6OZ73iBkdNjXUw8V|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e708193afc863de187691e5","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\RULES.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\\\RULES.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":192,"output":379,"cacheRead":119168,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119739,"cost":{"input":0.00048000000000000007,"output":0.005685,"cacheRead":0.029792,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.035957}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774980197262,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6691c88193bc298072e26db402"}}
{"type":"message","id":"d1dc5a58","parentId":"5ae6f260","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:28.627Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_YedjodyIKxlnvnFACtZfTB9a|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e2c819397fb97714d2b6b35","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 TTS Polish Output Validator Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the validation contract for per-batch `tts_polish` outputs inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\n`tts_polish_output_validator` validates one `tts_polish` batch output before that batch is allowed into the canonical `tts_polished.json` merge flow.\n\nIts job is to ensure that each polish batch result is structurally sound, preserves scene identity/order, preserves original narration reference, and does not introduce unacceptable semantic drift.\n\n---\n\n## Core principle\n\nThe unit of dispatch is the `tts_polish` batch.\n\nThe unit of semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch.\n\nThe preferred unit of correction is the affected subset of scenes within the batch, when possible.\n\nOnly approved batch outputs should be passed to `tts_polish_merger`.\n\n---\n\n## Validation architecture\n\nThis validator should use a two-layer model:\n\n### Layer 1 — deterministic Python validation\nChecks structural integrity and obvious drift signals.\n\n### Layer 2 — optional semantic review\nUsed only when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unacceptable without interpretation.\n\nThe semantic review layer is supervisory support, not autonomous final policy.\n\n---\n\n## Scope of deterministic validation\n\nFor one batch result, the deterministic layer should check:\n- JSON/object shape is valid\n- required top-level fields exist\n- `scenes` exists and is non-empty\n- expected scene count is preserved\n- scene order is preserved\n- `scene_id` mapping is preserved\n- every scene contains required fields\n- `narration_original` is preserved as the original input narration\n- `narration_tts` exists and is non-empty\n- obvious eaten words / unauthorized additions / scene mismatch signals\n- whether the batch should be approved, repaired by scene subset, regenerated, or escalated to semantic review\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\n`tts_polish_output_validator` does **not**:\n- decide final retry policy by itself\n- merge batch outputs\n- rewrite polished scenes directly\n- replace downstream audio validation\n- act as a freeform stylistic reviewer\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe validator should receive enough information to compare one polish batch output against its source polish batch.\n\n### Minimum expected input\n- run/job context sufficient for logging/reference\n- `batch_id`\n- source batch scenes\n- `tts_polish` batch output path or loaded object\n- required field specification / contract assumptions\n\n---\n\n## Output shape (draft)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"approved_for_merge\": true,\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_004\",\n  \"classification\": \"ok\",\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": [],\n  \"stats\": {\n    \"scene_count\": 5,\n    \"changed_scene_count\": 3,\n    \"flagged_scene_count\": 0\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Classification candidates\n- `ok`\n- `structural_patch`\n- `scene_subset_repair`\n- `batch_regenerate`\n- `needs_semantic_review`\n- `fatal_contract_error`\n\nThese are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\n\n---\n\n## Initial classification policy (v1)\n\nA practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\n- isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\n- localized clear problems in specific scenes -> `scene_subset_repair`\n- broad compromise across the batch -> `batch_regenerate`\n- meaningful but ambiguous semantic change -> `needs_semantic_review`\n- unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\n\nThis policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\n\n---\n\n## Failure classification intent\n\n### `structural_patch`\nUse when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk.\n\nTypical examples:\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\n- small metadata inconsistency\n- malformed scene wrapper without meaningful semantic uncertainty\n\n### `scene_subset_repair`\nUse when specific scenes in the batch clearly need correction while the rest of the batch remains usable.\n\nTypical examples:\n- eaten words in one or two scenes\n- unauthorized additions in one or two scenes\n- one scene mapped incorrectly\n- one scene with obviously unsafe polish while the rest is sound\n\n### `batch_regenerate`\nUse when the batch output is too compromised to trust targeted repair.\n\nTypical examples:\n- widespread drift across scenes\n- many eaten/additional content failures across the batch\n- scene ordering/mapping compromised broadly\n- multiple combined failures that undermine trust in the batch as a whole\n\n### `needs_semantic_review`\nUse when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely determine whether the change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable meaning drift.\n\nTypical examples:\n- wording changed significantly without obvious addition/deletion\n- abbreviation/ordinal/term normalization may be valid but is semantically uncertain\n- language-specific oral adaptation changed phrasing in a way that requires interpretation\n\n### `fatal_contract_error`\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\n\nTypical examples:\n- unreadable JSON\n- missing top-level required structure\n- missing scene list\n- unusable mapping between input and output scenes\n\n---\n\n## Validation principles\n\n- deterministic checks should catch obvious breakage and drift first\n- semantic review should be used sparingly, only when needed\n- already-approved scenes should not be disturbed because another scene in the batch failed\n- the validator should help the supervisor target only the affected scenes when possible\n- semantic review informs supervisory control; it does not replace it\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- run deterministic validation on each `tts_polish` batch output\n- inspect the returned classification and error list\n- invoke semantic review only when classification indicates ambiguity\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\n- only pass approved batches to `tts_polish_merger`\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\n\n`tts_polish` should not own this validator or self-manage retry policy.\n\nHowever, the supervisor may use validator findings to reinvoke `tts_polish` with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes within the batch.\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- per-batch validation as the orchestration unit\n- per-scene sensitivity inside the batch\n- deterministic validation plus optional semantic review\n- scene-subset repair as the preferred correction mode when possible\n- merge only after batch approval\n\nNext step: create the real OpenClaw workspace for `tts_polish` and later implement the deterministic validator layer.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980208506}}
{"type":"message","id":"25ba35ec","parentId":"d1dc5a58","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:28.757Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_MY2jfyx5pLpGsfMyN4lhU3Nd|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e40819389ef0d5862e2f0d4","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 TTS Polish Semantic Reviewer Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and review contract of the semantic reviewer used for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is a narrow semantic-arbitration operator used only when deterministic validation cannot safely decide whether a `tts_polish` change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable semantic drift.\n\nIts job is to judge ambiguous polish changes and return an actionable recommendation to the S1 Supervisor.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is:\n\n> Judge whether borderline `tts_polish` changes preserve the intended meaning and information of the original scene while remaining acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\n\nThis reviewer is not a main pipeline operator. It is an auxiliary supervisory support layer.\n\n---\n\n## When it is invoked\n\nThis reviewer should be invoked only when the deterministic `tts_polish_output_validator` returns a classification such as `needs_semantic_review`.\n\nIt should not be called for:\n- clean approvals\n- obvious structural failures\n- obvious eaten-word / unauthorized-addition failures already classifiable without interpretation\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nThe reviewer should receive only the minimum material needed to arbitrate the ambiguous case.\n\n### Minimum expected input\n- run/job context sufficient for reference\n- `batch_id`\n- affected subset of scenes only\n- for each affected scene:\n  - `scene_id`\n  - `narration_original`\n  - `narration_tts`\n- validator flags / ambiguity reasons\n- relevant language or channel polish rules when needed\n\nThe reviewer should not be overloaded with full-sector context unless strictly necessary.\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nThe reviewer should return a per-scene judgment structure that the supervisor can act on directly.\n\n### Draft output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_004\",\n  \"reviewed_scenes\": [\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_012\",\n      \"judgment\": \"acceptable_tts_normalization\",\n      \"reason\": \"The wording changed, but meaning and factual content remain intact.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"approve_scene\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_013\",\n      \"judgment\": \"unsafe_meaning_drift\",\n      \"reason\": \"The polished version introduces content not present in the original.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"repair_scene\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n### Judgment candidates\n- `acceptable_tts_normalization`\n- `unsafe_meaning_drift`\n- `unclear_but_repair_preferred`\n\n### Recommended action candidates\n- `approve_scene`\n- `repair_scene`\n- `regenerate_batch_if_needed`\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` should **not**:\n- perform the original polish itself\n- validate structural JSON/output shape\n- decide batching strategy\n- decide retry policy by itself\n- merge outputs\n- review the whole pipeline by default\n- behave like a creative rewriting agent\n\nIt exists only to arbitrate semantic ambiguity in borderline polish cases.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to the deterministic validator\n\nThe deterministic validator should:\n- catch obvious breakage\n- catch obvious semantic violations when possible\n- escalate only ambiguous cases\n\nThe semantic reviewer should:\n- judge the ambiguous cases only\n- avoid re-litigating clear structural failures already decided upstream\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- decide when semantic review is needed\n- pass only the affected scenes for review when possible\n- interpret the reviewer output\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\n\nThe reviewer informs supervisory judgment; it does not replace it.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\n\nThis reviewer does not own the `tts_polish` loop.\n\nHowever, its output may be used by the supervisor to send targeted repair feedback back to `tts_polish` for specific scenes within a batch.\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good reviewer output should:\n- be narrow and decisive\n- explain why the change is acceptable or unsafe\n- focus on semantic preservation, not stylistic preference\n- avoid unnecessary escalation\n- return recommendations the supervisor can act on directly\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the role of semantic review in the `tts_polish` loop\n- the input/output shape for borderline scene review\n- the distinction between deterministic validation and semantic arbitration\n- the reviewer as an auxiliary support layer to the supervisor\n\nNext step: create the reviewer workspace and then perform a systemic S1 review to align contracts, supervisor docs, runtime expectations, and scene bible implications.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980208628}}
{"type":"message","id":"4248a28e","parentId":"25ba35ec","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:28.885Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_evEJmo7q3BmbyTxwv7eHrm0m|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e4881939dd9862cd4584ec1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# IDENTITY.md\n\n## Name\nop_s1_tts_polish\n\n## One-Sentence Identity\nOperador do S1 responsável por transformar pequenas sequências de cenas em versões optimizadas para TTS, preservando significado, informação e ordem enquanto melhora legibilidade oral e pronúncia.\n\n## Mission\nTransformar a narração original de cada cena numa versão optimizada para TTS, preservando integralmente significado, informação e cobertura textual, enquanto aplica apenas ajustes de legibilidade oral, pronúncia e normalização necessários para voz sintética.\n\n## Position in Hierarchy\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- Não é supervisor\n- Não é validator\n- Não é scene director\n- Não é gerador de áudio\n\n## Core Responsibility\nAjustar a formulação oral de pequenas sequências de cenas para TTS sem alterar conteúdo narrativo, cobertura ou ordem das cenas.\n\n## What It Does Not Do\n- Não reestrutura a narrativa\n- Não muda a ordem das cenas\n- Não faz batching\n- Não define retry policy\n- Não valida o próprio output\n- Não gera áudio\n- Não cria timestamps/alinhamento\n- Não faz visual planning\n\n## Working Mode\n- Opera em pequenos batches ordenados de cenas\n- Mantém sensibilidade cena a cena dentro do batch\n- Prioriza preservação semântica antes de fluidez\n- Recebe feedback estruturado do supervisor quando houver repair\n- Não deve improvisar fora da sua missão e boundaries\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980208758}}
{"type":"message","id":"a5b3cf45","parentId":"4248a28e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:29.003Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_G0241kmmdo4MlWwhqi4RUJ63|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e508193be118a1c4aa35a7d","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish`, the S1 operator responsible for safe TTS-oriented oral normalization.\n\nYour job is to improve how scene narration will sound in synthetic voice output without changing what the narration says.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve meaning and information exactly\n2. Preserve scene identity and order exactly\n3. Preserve `narration_original` exactly as reference\n4. Improve pronunciation-readiness and readability for TTS only where necessary\n5. Avoid unnecessary rewriting\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like a controlled oral-normalization operator, not like a creative writer.\n- You are not here to improve the story itself.\n- You are here to make the narration safer and cleaner for voice synthesis.\n- Prefer minimal necessary change over aggressive polishing.\n- If a change is not clearly justified, do not make it.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good result:\n- keeps the same meaning\n- keeps the same scene order\n- keeps each scene tied to the same `scene_id`\n- improves readability for spoken output\n- handles things like abbreviations, units, ordinals, and oral awkwardness carefully\n- stays structurally easy to validate\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad output includes:\n- paraphrasing the narration freely\n- removing details because they sound awkward\n- adding clarifying words not present in the original\n- shifting tone or intent\n- acting as if you can rewrite scenes to sound more dramatic\n- changing multiple scenes more than necessary\n\n## Repair Mindset\n\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, repair only the affected scenes unless the instruction explicitly says otherwise.\nDo not redesign unaffected scenes.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980208885}}
{"type":"message","id":"a84e6528","parentId":"a5b3cf45","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:29.123Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_WifxIKjJLGd2SzifUlRQkriS|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e5881938ef3967499702d39","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# RULES.md\n\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Never change meaning**\n   - Do not alter the meaning, implication, factual content, or narrative intention of the original scene.\n\n2. **Never add or remove information**\n   - Do not eat words, compress ideas, expand ideas, embellish, summarize, or paraphrase beyond what is strictly necessary for TTS normalization.\n\n3. **Preserve scene identity and order**\n   - Keep the same `scene_id` mapping.\n   - Keep the same scene order.\n   - Do not merge or split scenes.\n\n4. **Preserve original reference**\n   - `narration_original` must remain the original source narration for the scene.\n\n5. **Optimize narrowly for TTS**\n   - Apply only the minimum necessary changes for pronunciation, readability, oral clarity, abbreviations, ordinals, units, and similar TTS concerns.\n\n6. **Do not absorb another layer's job**\n   - Do not re-decide scene structure.\n   - Do not validate your own output.\n   - Do not generate audio.\n   - Do not create timestamps/alignment.\n\n7. **Respect batch discipline**\n   - Operate only on the scenes provided in the assigned batch.\n   - Do not act as if you own the whole screenplay.\n\n8. **Prefer safe minimalism**\n   - If a change is not clearly necessary for TTS improvement, prefer not to make it.\n\n## Output Fields Required Per Scene\n\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\n## Optional Fields\n\n- `changes`\n\n## Quality Standard\n\nA good output should:\n- sound better in TTS than the original raw narration\n- preserve meaning fully\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\n- remain narrow rather than becoming stylistic rewriting\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980209003}}
{"type":"message","id":"7df8d518","parentId":"a84e6528","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:29.250Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_SihZM4mOkLEET9x95lblFtVS|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e608193b38782574788d4cb","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# IDENTITY.md\n\n## Name\nop_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\n\n## One-Sentence Identity\nRevisor semântico auxiliar do S1 responsável por arbitrar casos ambíguos do `tts_polish`, distinguindo normalização legítima para TTS de drift semântico indevido.\n\n## Mission\nJulgar alterações borderline feitas pelo `tts_polish` e devolver ao supervisor um parecer accionável sobre se a mudança preserva significado e informação ou se precisa de repair.\n\n## Position in Hierarchy\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- Atua como auxiliar do loop de `tts_polish`\n- Não é supervisor\n- Não é validator estrutural\n- Não é operador principal do pipeline\n\n## Core Responsibility\nArbitrar casos semanticamente ambíguos em que a validação determinística não consegue decidir sozinha se uma mudança de TTS polish é aceitável.\n\n## What It Does Not Do\n- Não faz TTS polish original\n- Não valida estrutura JSON\n- Não define retry policy\n- Não faz merge\n- Não revê o pipeline inteiro por defeito\n- Não age como rewriter criativo\n\n## Working Mode\n- Entra apenas em casos ambíguos\n- Recebe apenas o subconjunto de cenas afectadas quando possível\n- Foca em preservação semântica, não em preferência estilística\n- Devolve julgamento accionável para o supervisor\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980209127}}
{"type":"message","id":"72fffc63","parentId":"7df8d518","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:29.365Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_0cbJ022VJDNDxnqkLy7xdl1r|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e688193b191be3c96c5ec94","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`, a narrow semantic reviewer used only for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases.\n\nYour task is to judge whether a polished scene remains faithful to the original scene while still being acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve meaning and information\n2. Distinguish acceptable oral normalization from unsafe drift\n3. Return a clear actionable recommendation for the supervisor\n4. Stay narrow and scene-specific\n5. Avoid stylistic over-analysis\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like an arbitrator, not like a writer.\n- Do not ask whether the new version is nicer.\n- Ask whether it still says the same thing.\n- Ask whether the changes are justified by TTS needs.\n- If the answer is semantically uncertain, prefer repair over permissive approval.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good review:\n- explains why a change is acceptable or unsafe\n- focuses on meaning preservation\n- does not drift into structural validation or batch orchestration\n- gives the supervisor a next action that is easy to apply\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad review includes:\n- rewriting the scene instead of judging it\n- debating style instead of semantic preservation\n- rechecking obvious structural failures that should have been caught earlier\n- giving vague recommendations with no clear next action\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980209250}}
{"type":"message","id":"29195a43","parentId":"72fffc63","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:29.495Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_VO5ZyumE6OZ73iBkdNjXUw8V|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c6f1e708193afc863de187691e5","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# RULES.md\n\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Judge semantics, not taste**\n   - Your job is to evaluate whether meaning/information was preserved, not whether the wording is prettier.\n\n2. **Stay narrow**\n   - Review only the ambiguous scenes provided.\n   - Do not widen the scope unless explicitly required.\n\n3. **Do not become the polisher**\n   - You are not here to rewrite the text yourself.\n   - You are here to judge whether the existing polish is acceptable or unsafe.\n\n4. **Do not re-litigate structural issues**\n   - Structural/obvious failures belong to deterministic validation.\n   - Focus on ambiguity that requires interpretation.\n\n5. **Return actionable judgments**\n   - Your output must help the supervisor decide what to do next.\n\n6. **Prefer semantic safety over stylistic generosity**\n   - If a change is semantically questionable, lean toward repair rather than permissive approval.\n\n## Judgment Goals\n\nFor each scene under review, determine whether the polish is:\n- acceptable TTS normalization\n- unsafe semantic drift\n- unclear enough that repair is still the safer action\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980209365}}
{"type":"message","id":"13c40aa5","parentId":"29195a43","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:03:49.455Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vou consolidar esta parte criando os contratos que faltam e alinhando o supervisor/workspace para deixar explícito o lane do reviewer.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c759a8c8193a3a195e952938c33\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_35aeodfpK0aryYH4YZ4cjNPp|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c7657dc8193b6a0a9e56f6a9445","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_tts_polish_output_validator_runtime_contract.md","content":"# S1 TTS Polish Output Validator Runtime Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the intended runtime role of the per-batch `tts_polish` validation layer inside S1._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish_output_validator` is the intended per-batch validation layer for `tts_polish` outputs inside S1.\n\nIts role is to validate one polish batch before that batch is accepted into canonical merge flow.\n\nThis contract exists to make the runtime architecture explicit even if the deterministic validator implementation is not yet fully extracted as a dedicated supervisor skill.\n\n---\n\n## Canonical architectural rule\n\nThe `tts_polish` lane should follow the same architectural shape as the `scene_director` lane:\n- batch planning\n- IO adapter bridge\n- operator execution\n- per-batch validation\n- optional semantic review only for ambiguous cases\n- merge only after approval\n- whole-artifact validation after merge\n\nThis means `tts_polish_output_validator` is a canonical architectural component, not an optional nice-to-have.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nThis component sits between:\n- `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n\nAnd may escalate ambiguous cases to:\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\n---\n\n## Ownership\n\n### Owned by\n- S1 Supervisor as a validation layer under supervisory control\n\n### Not owned by\n- `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n\nThe validator classifies and gates.\nThe supervisor decides.\n\n---\n\n## Responsibilities\n\nThe validator should:\n- validate batch-level structure\n- validate required fields per scene\n- validate scene identity/order preservation\n- validate preservation of `narration_original`\n- validate presence of `narration_tts`\n- detect obvious eaten words / unauthorized additions / scene mismatch signals\n- classify the batch as:\n  - approvable\n  - repairable by subset\n  - broad regenerate candidate\n  - semantically ambiguous and needing review\n  - fatally malformed\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\nThe validator must **not**:\n- merge batches\n- decide final retry policy\n- rewrite polished scenes itself\n- replace downstream audio validation\n- act as a freeform stylistic reviewer\n\n---\n\n## Validation layering rule\n\n### Layer 1 — deterministic validation\nShould catch:\n- shape failures\n- identity/order failures\n- obvious drift/addition/removal failures\n- straightforward subset repair candidates\n\n### Layer 2 — optional semantic review\nShould be invoked only when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unsafe.\n\n---\n\n## Review escalation rule\n\nThe semantic reviewer should only receive:\n- affected scenes\n- relevant ambiguity reasons\n- minimal necessary context\n\nIt should not be used as a generic second-pass reviewer for all batches.\n\n---\n\n## Merge rule\n\nOnly approved batch outputs should be passed to `tts_polish_merger`.\nRejected, ambiguous-unreviewed, or malformed outputs must not enter the canonical merge path.\n\n---\n\n## Architectural note\n\nAt the time of this contract, the conceptual contract for this component already exists in:\n- `docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n\nThis runtime contract exists to make explicit that the component is part of the canonical runtime architecture and should eventually be represented with equivalent runtime clarity to the `scene_director_output_validator` lane.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_tts_polish_output_validator_runtime_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 TTS Polish Output Validator Runtime Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the intended runtime role of the per-batch `tts_polish` validation layer inside S1._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `tts_polish_output_validator` is the intended per-batch validation layer for `tts_polish` outputs inside S1.\\n\\nIts role is to validate one polish batch before that batch is accepted into canonical merge flow.\\n\\nThis contract exists to make the runtime architecture explicit even if the deterministic validator implementation is not yet fully extracted as a dedicated supervisor skill.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical architectural rule\\n\\nThe `tts_polish` lane should follow the same architectural shape as the `scene_director` lane:\\n- batch planning\\n- IO adapter bridge\\n- operator execution\\n- per-batch validation\\n- optional semantic review only for ambiguous cases\\n- merge only after approval\\n- whole-artifact validation after merge\\n\\nThis means `tts_polish_output_validator` is a canonical architectural component, not an optional nice-to-have.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nThis component sits between:\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- `tts_polish_merger`\\n\\nAnd may escalate ambiguous cases to:\\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ownership\\n\\n### Owned by\\n- S1 Supervisor as a validation layer under supervisory control\\n\\n### Not owned by\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\\n- `tts_polish_merger`\\n\\nThe validator classifies and gates.\\nThe supervisor decides.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Responsibilities\\n\\nThe validator should:\\n- validate batch-level structure\\n- validate required fields per scene\\n- validate scene identity/order preservation\\n- validate preservation of `narration_original`\\n- validate presence of `narration_tts`\\n- detect obvious eaten words / unauthorized additions / scene mismatch signals\\n- classify the batch as:\\n  - approvable\\n  - repairable by subset\\n  - broad regenerate candidate\\n  - semantically ambiguous and needing review\\n  - fatally malformed\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\nThe validator must **not**:\\n- merge batches\\n- decide final retry policy\\n- rewrite polished scenes itself\\n- replace downstream audio validation\\n- act as a freeform stylistic reviewer\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Validation layering rule\\n\\n### Layer 1 — deterministic validation\\nShould catch:\\n- shape failures\\n- identity/order failures\\n- obvious drift/addition/removal failures\\n- straightforward subset repair candidates\\n\\n### Layer 2 — optional semantic review\\nShould be invoked only when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unsafe.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Review escalation rule\\n\\nThe semantic reviewer should only receive:\\n- affected scenes\\n- relevant ambiguity reasons\\n- minimal necessary context\\n\\nIt should not be used as a generic second-pass reviewer for all batches.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Merge rule\\n\\nOnly approved batch outputs should be passed to `tts_polish_merger`.\\nRejected, ambiguous-unreviewed, or malformed outputs must not enter the canonical merge path.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Architectural note\\n\\nAt the time of this contract, the conceptual contract for this component already exists in:\\n- `docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\\n\\nThis runtime contract exists to make explicit that the component is part of the canonical runtime architecture and should eventually be represented with equivalent runtime clarity to the `scene_director_output_validator` lane.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":4404,"output":876,"cacheRead":119552,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":124832,"cost":{"input":0.01101,"output":0.01314,"cacheRead":0.029887999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.054038}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774980210103,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0c72b10481939619935d7a900077"}}
