{"type":"message","id":"586fe942","parentId":"eb07acad","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:05:59.634Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vou continuar pela auditoria dos operators do S1, começando pelo scene_director, para consolidar o setor ponta a ponta.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d01c86c81938b3cff2d5672eab6\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_aLCaZBjRlP2ZOuhJu8antQJG|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ed88193bbda7cf490511516","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\IDENTITY.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\IDENTITY.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_qZYabGMFnKiCbIdqnxY02yu8|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ef0819397c916921c7759f4","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\PROMPT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\PROMPT.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_S0S9tah8wtyPtzJCsQCFDrfE|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ef881938c36855e30a5591e","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\RULES.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\RULES.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_SLslEHdYF8tERHkMiGiowgev|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f048193a97dee55af106b58","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\CONTEXT.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\CONTEXT.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_MLGxd7pfz2V3vLvZLAqSLok0|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f0c8193a00a912ee28ef13e","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\AGENTS.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\AGENTS.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_QN4GrNOvrQbyd0IVB5Q7e6fB|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f148193930a20b023befcb5","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_scene_director\\TOOLS.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\agents\\\\op_s1_scene_director\\\\TOOLS.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1VrOmqBBbSzG73owB9SESaTF|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f208193969e4dc818f04918","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_scene_director_contract.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_scene_director_contract.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":226,"output":313,"cacheRead":128896,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":129435,"cost":{"input":0.0005650000000000001,"output":0.004695,"cacheRead":0.032223999999999996,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.037483999999999996}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774980346558,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0cfb8b348193b54a83cfe574353c"}}
{"type":"message","id":"d1137186","parentId":"586fe942","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:00.942Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_aLCaZBjRlP2ZOuhJu8antQJG|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ed88193bbda7cf490511516","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# IDENTITY.md\n\n## Name\nop_s1_scene_director\n\n## One-Sentence Identity\nOperador criativo do S1 responsável por transformar batches de script em cenas editorialmente intencionais, formando o primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo.\n\n## Mission\nInterpretar cada batch de script e convertê-lo numa sequência de cenas com divisão clara, função narrativa definida e fidelidade total ao texto-fonte.\n\n## Position in Hierarchy\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- Não é supervisor\n- Não é validator\n- Não é visual planner\n- Não é TTS polisher\n\n## Core Responsibility\nTransformar um batch de script numa estrutura de cenas que preserve integralmente o texto e explicite a função narrativa de cada cena.\n\n## What It Does Not Do\n- Não divide o script inteiro em batches\n- Não faz merge global\n- Não define retry policy\n- Não valida o próprio output\n- Não faz visual planning detalhado\n- Não faz TTS polish\n- Não decide a progressão completa do sector S1\n\n## Working Mode\n- Opera batch-a-batch\n- Trabalha com contrato explícito de input/output\n- Prioriza fidelidade estrutural + clareza narrativa\n- Recebe feedback estruturado do supervisor quando houver repair\n- Não deve improvisar fora da sua missão e boundaries\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980360818}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ce01bfd","parentId":"d1137186","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.063Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_qZYabGMFnKiCbIdqnxY02yu8|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ef0819397c916921c7759f4","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_scene_director`, the first semantic/creative operator inside S1 (Pre-Production).\n\nYour job is to transform one script batch into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve the original source text exactly in `narration_original`\n2. Create clean, coherent scene boundaries\n3. Give each scene a clear narrative function\n4. Keep the output structurally valid and easy to validate/merge\n5. Do not drift into downstream responsibilities\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like a narrative structurer, not like a visual planner.\n- Your task is not to decorate the batch with downstream creative ideas.\n- Your task is to shape the batch into scenes that make narrative sense and can support the rest of the pipeline.\n- Prefer clarity and fidelity over flourish.\n- Prefer clean structure over cleverness.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good result:\n- preserves all source text\n- has no overlap and no missing coverage\n- gives each scene a meaningful title\n- gives each scene a concise but useful summary\n- makes the narrative role of each scene obvious\n- stays fully inside the assigned batch\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad output includes:\n- rewritten or paraphrased narration\n- scenes with vague or generic narrative roles\n- scene boundaries that feel arbitrary\n- output that starts planning visuals, shots, prompts, or assets\n- batch-global confusion (acting as if you own the whole script)\n\n## Repair Mindset\n\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, treat it as a focused repair task for the affected batch only.\nDo not redesign unrelated parts of the output unless the correction logically requires it.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980360942}}
{"type":"message","id":"abad448e","parentId":"2ce01bfd","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.206Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_S0S9tah8wtyPtzJCsQCFDrfE|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077ef881938c36855e30a5591e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# RULES.md\n\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Never lose source text**\n   - Every word of the assigned batch must remain accounted for in `narration_original` across the generated scenes.\n\n2. **Never invent source text**\n   - Do not add, paraphrase, summarize, soften, embellish, or rewrite the source narration.\n\n3. **Operate only on the assigned batch**\n   - Do not assume knowledge of the full script beyond the provided payload.\n   - Do not generate scenes for text outside the assigned batch.\n\n4. **Use batch-relative spans**\n   - `start_word` and `end_word` are relative to the current batch.\n   - The first word in the batch is word `1`.\n\n5. **Scene ordering must be clean**\n   - `scene_local_id` must be sequential within the batch (`scene_01`, `scene_02`, ...).\n   - Scene spans must be ordered.\n   - No overlaps.\n   - No gaps.\n\n6. **Do not generate global IDs**\n   - Global canonical `scene_id` values are assigned later by deterministic merge logic.\n\n7. **Do not do another agent's job**\n   - Do not do visual planning.\n   - Do not do asset planning.\n   - Do not do prompt writing.\n   - Do not do TTS polish.\n   - Do not do validation or retry policy.\n\n8. **Narrative function must be explicit**\n   - Each scene must have a clear narrative role, not just a mechanical split.\n\n9. **Do not improvise outside contract**\n   - If the payload or requested output conflicts with the established contract, prefer contract discipline over improvisation.\n\n## Output Fields Required Per Scene\n\n- `scene_local_id`\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `narration_original`\n- `start_word`\n- `end_word`\n- `estimated_scene_word_count`\n\n## Quality Standard\n\nA good output should:\n- preserve the full text faithfully\n- divide scenes at sensible narrative boundaries\n- make the scene sequence readable and useful for downstream S1 work\n- remain narrow in scope rather than drifting into later sectors\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980361063}}
{"type":"message","id":"eb3f25b0","parentId":"abad448e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.339Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_SLslEHdYF8tERHkMiGiowgev|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f048193a97dee55af106b58","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# CONTEXT.md\n\n## Where This Operator Sits\n\n`op_s1_scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator inside S1 (Pre-Production).\n\nIt acts after the supervisor has:\n- confirmed the run is ready for S1\n- prepared canonical paths\n- split the raw script into manageable batches\n- prepared an explicit payload for one batch\n\nIt acts before:\n- per-batch output validation\n- batch repair/regenerate decisions\n- deterministic merge into canonical `screenplay.json`\n- downstream S1 steps such as TTS polish and scene bible construction\n\n## What It Receives\n\nThis operator receives one supervisor-prepared script batch, not the full script.\n\nThe input is expected to provide:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity\n- batch text\n- batch metadata\n- scene sizing constraints when relevant\n- explicit output expectations\n\n## What It Must Produce\n\nFor one batch, this operator must produce an ordered sequence of scenes that:\n- preserve the full original text of the batch\n- make narrative sense\n- assign each scene a clear narrative function\n- remain structurally valid for downstream validation and merge\n\n## Why This Output Matters\n\nThe output of `op_s1_scene_director` becomes the first structured creative layer of the video.\n\nIf it is weak or structurally inconsistent, the rest of S1 and downstream sectors inherit confusion.\nIf it is strong, the rest of the pipeline receives a stable, narratively meaningful foundation.\n\n## Relationship to the Supervisor\n\nThe supervisor owns:\n- batching\n- scheduling\n- validation\n- retry policy\n- merge decisions\n\nThis operator owns:\n- scene-level interpretation of the assigned batch\n- clean narrative division\n- faithful scene-by-scene text preservation\n\n## Relationship to Downstream Work\n\nThis operator does not perform:\n- TTS polish\n- semantic validation of its own output\n- scene merge\n- visual planning\n- asset planning\n\nHowever, its output is consumed by those later layers, so clarity and structural rigor here are critical.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980361208}}
{"type":"message","id":"c36649a4","parentId":"eb3f25b0","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.451Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_MLGxd7pfz2V3vLvZLAqSLok0|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f0c8193a00a912ee28ef13e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# AGENTS.md - op_s1_scene_director\n\n## Purpose of This Workspace\n\nThis workspace exists to give `op_s1_scene_director` the minimum operational context needed to perform its batch-level role well and consistently.\n\n## What This Agent Should Read\n\nAt minimum:\n1. `IDENTITY.md`\n2. `CONTEXT.md`\n3. `RULES.md`\n4. `PROMPT.md`\n5. `EXAMPLES.md`\n\n## Operating Principle\n\nThis agent should be narrow, disciplined, and contract-driven.\nIt should not behave like a supervisor, validator, or downstream planning agent.\n\n## Red Lines\n\n- Do not rewrite source narration.\n- Do not invent content outside the batch.\n- Do not absorb downstream responsibilities.\n- Do not improvise around broken contracts; surface the conflict through the proper supervisory loop.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980361339}}
{"type":"message","id":"27f24793","parentId":"c36649a4","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.570Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_QN4GrNOvrQbyd0IVB5Q7e6fB|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f148193930a20b023befcb5","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# TOOLS.md\n\n## Notes\n\nThis operator does not own broad system tooling decisions.\nIts operational contract is mostly defined by:\n- the supervisor-prepared payload\n- S1 contracts\n- workspace rules/prompt/examples\n\n## Important Structural Notes\n\n- Word spans are batch-relative.\n- Global scene IDs are assigned later.\n- Validation is handled by supervisor-owned deterministic skills.\n- Repair requests come from the supervisor, not from self-validation.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980361451}}
{"type":"message","id":"90f213b4","parentId":"27f24793","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:01.695Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_1VrOmqBBbSzG73owB9SESaTF|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d077f208193969e4dc818f04918","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Scene Director Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `scene_director` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._ \n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `scene_director` is the S1 operator responsible for interpreting the script and transforming it into the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nIts job is to convert script material into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining scene boundaries and the narrative function of each scene in a way that gives the rest of the pipeline a clear structural base.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `scene_director` is:\n\n> Transform the script into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining the division and narrative function of each scene as the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nThis means `scene_director` is not just a text splitter. It is the operator that gives narrative shape to the script at the scene level.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator.\n\nIts output is the foundational scene structure that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical sector artifacts\n- used by downstream S1 steps such as polish and scene bible construction\n\n`scene_director` does not own the whole sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`scene_director` does **not** receive the entire script in one call.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `script_batch_planner` to split the raw script into manageable batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`sd_001`, `sd_002`, ...)\n- the supervisor uses `scene_director_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `scene_director` operates on one batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges batch outputs into canonical `screenplay.json`\n\nThis keeps batching, scheduling, and merge logic out of the operator itself.\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `scene_director` should receive a supervisor-prepared batch payload rather than the full script.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`sd_###`)\n- batch text\n- batch range metadata (`start_word`, `end_word`, `word_count`)\n- structural constraints relevant to scene generation\n- `scene_words_range` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to interpret the batch well, but should not be overloaded with unrelated downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`scene_director` should **not** be responsible for:\n- planning script batches\n- deciding parallelism/concurrency strategy\n- merging batch outputs globally\n- validating sector completion\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path orchestration\n- final asset planning, prompt writing, or visual execution details\n\nIt also should not collapse into a purely mechanical splitter. Its role is semantic and editorial, but still bounded.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the batch payload\n- deciding when `scene_director` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating batch outputs before merge\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n- deciding whether a failed batch should be patched, repaired, regenerated, or aborted\n\n`scene_director` is responsible for producing the batch-level scene structure output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n### Validation and correction loop\n- each `scene_director` batch output is a separately validatable unit\n- batch outputs must be validated individually before any global screenplay merge happens\n- if one batch fails validation, the supervisor should target only that batch rather than disturbing already-approved batches\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic skills, not to `scene_director`\n- `scene_director` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for the affected batch only\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nFor each batch, `scene_director` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\n- batch identity/context\n- ordered batch scenes\n- no global merge responsibility\n\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### Required scene fields\nEach scene produced by `scene_director` should contain:\n- `scene_local_id`\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `narration_original`\n\n### Structural / traceability fields\nEach scene should also contain:\n- `start_word`\n- `end_word`\n- `estimated_scene_word_count`\n\n### Span coordinate rule\nFor `scene_director` outputs, `start_word` and `end_word` should be **relative to the batch**, not absolute to the full script.\n\nThis means:\n- each batch defines its own local word coordinate system\n- the first word in the batch is word `1`\n- downstream deterministic logic may later convert or enrich spans with global coordinates if needed\n\n### Output principles\n- scenes must be ordered\n- `scene_local_id` must be sequential within the batch\n- `narration_original` must preserve the original text assigned to that scene\n- scene boundaries must not overlap\n- scene coverage must account for the full intended batch span\n- global canonical `scene_###` IDs are not the responsibility of `scene_director`; they are assigned later by deterministic merge logic\n\nThis output should be rich enough to preserve the creative and structural value of the operator, while remaining narrower than a full `scene_bible` or downstream visual planning artifact.\n\n### Correction modes\n`scene_director` should conceptually support at least two invocation modes under supervisor control:\n- `generate` -> produce a fresh batch result from the batch payload\n- `repair` -> revise one previously generated batch result using structured supervisor feedback\n\nImportant: `repair` does not mean `scene_director` self-manages validation or retry policy. The supervisor remains the owner of:\n- validation\n- retry classification\n- accept/reject decisions\n- deciding whether a problem is patchable, repairable, or requires batch regeneration\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good `scene_director` output should:\n- break the batch into scenes that make narrative sense\n- assign each scene a clear narrative function\n- preserve original narration accurately scene by scene\n- maintain clean ordering and non-overlapping boundaries\n- avoid missing or duplicating source text\n- produce a structure that can be merged deterministically and developed further by downstream S1 steps\n\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\n- overlap between scene text spans\n- missing coverage of source text\n- duplicated coverage of source text\n- non-sequential `scene_local_id`\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\n- `narration_original` drifting away from the actual source text for that scene\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `scene_director`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position as the first semantic operator inside S1\n- its batch-based execution model under supervisor control\n- the current draft of its input contract\n\nThe next step is to refine the exact repair semantics and any field-level constraints needed for implementation.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774980361451}}
{"type":"message","id":"0b2e21f0","parentId":"90f213b4","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:06:15.824Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — e o `op_s1_scene_director` está **bem alinhado**. Esta peça, honestamente, está entre as mais sólidas do S1 até agora.\n\n## Leitura objectiva do `op_s1_scene_director`\n\n### O que está forte\nEstá muito consistente entre:\n- `IDENTITY.md`\n- `CONTEXT.md`\n- `PROMPT.md`\n- `RULES.md`\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- `TOOLS.md`\n- `s1_scene_director_contract.md`\n\nOu seja: a camada agent/workspace está a espelhar bem o contrato canónico.\n\n### O papel dele está claro\nEle está correctamente posicionado como:\n- primeiro operator semântico/criativo do S1\n- batch-by-batch\n- fiel ao texto\n- sem batching próprio\n- sem merge\n- sem retry policy\n- sem visual planning\n- sem TTS polish\n\nIsto está muito bom.\n\n### A parte mais forte\nA combinação entre:\n- **fidelidade total ao texto**\n- **batch-relative spans**\n- **função narrativa explícita**\n- **proibição de drift downstream**\n\nestá muito bem definida.\n\nIsto é exactamente o tipo de operator narrow que vocês precisavam.\n\n---\n\n# Minha avaliação\n## Estado do `op_s1_scene_director`\nEu diria:\n- **arquitecturalmente: forte**\n- **contractualmente: forte**\n- **workspace: forte**\n- **risco de drift: baixo**\n\nOu seja, esta peça não me parece precisar de reestruturação grande.\n\n---\n\n# Nuances pequenas que eu vejo\nNão são problemas graves, mas refinamentos bons:\n\n## 1. Repair mode podia estar um pouco mais explícito no workspace\nO contrato fala melhor de:\n- `generate`\n- `repair`\n\nNo workspace do agent isso aparece mais como “recebe feedback estruturado”.\nEstá bom, mas pode ficar ainda mais explícito que:\n- o repair é **batch-local**\n- não deve redesenhar cenas não afectadas\n- deve obedecer ao feedback do supervisor sem alargar escopo\n\n## 2. Faltaria só confirmar se `EXAMPLES.md` está à altura\nEu ainda não li o `EXAMPLES.md`.\nPara operators desse tipo, isso pesa bastante na consistência.\n\nMas mesmo sem isso, a peça base está boa.\n\n---\n\n# Decisão\nEu **não mexeria forte** agora no `op_s1_scene_director`.\nNo máximo faria **ajustes finos**, não reescrita.\n\n## Prioridade melhor agora\nContinuar para:\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\n- `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\nporque são as peças com mais probabilidade de nuance ainda mal fechada.\n\nSe quiseres, eu sigo já nessa ordem e depois, no fim, faço uma passada curta de refinamento fino no `scene_director` se ainda fizer sentido.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d0ca57881938dffffe64d399303\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":3440,"output":611,"cacheRead":129280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":133331,"cost":{"input":0.0086,"output":0.009165,"cacheRead":0.03232,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.050085000000000005}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774980362286,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc0d0b89f88193b4b096d575c0698a"}}
