{"type":"message","id":"4a35de9b","parentId":"2d909b09","timestamp":"2026-03-31T18:30:47.334Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_QbVyMmLpyldcyAPnQsUeKTvF|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc12c57e7881938ec68758689f4377","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_polish_validator_contract.md","content":"# S1 Polish Validator Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic whole-polish validation layer inside S1._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `polish_validator` validates the canonical merged `tts_polished.json` against the canonical screenplay after approved polish batches have already been merged.\n\nIts role is to detect whether the TTS narration layer preserved scene identity, original reference, and semantic safety closely enough for S1 to complete safely.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nThis component sits after:\n- `tts_polish_output_validator`\n- optional `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n\nAnd before:\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- any supervisor retry decision triggered by polish-level failure\n\n---\n\n## Ownership\n\n### Owned by\n- S1 as a shared deterministic sector component\n\n### Not owned by\n- `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\nIt is a whole-artifact validator, not a batch dispatcher and not a semantic reviewer.\n\n---\n\n## Responsibilities\n\nThe validator should:\n- validate scene identity preservation using `scene_id`\n- validate scene order preservation\n- validate preservation of `narration_original`\n- validate presence of `narration_tts`\n- detect obvious eaten words\n- detect suspicious additions\n- expose affected scenes to the supervisor when possible\n- produce a structured result usable by the supervisor and retry planner\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\nThe validator must **not**:\n- replace the earlier per-batch polish validation lane\n- replace semantic review for ambiguous cases\n- invoke retries\n- merge batches\n- invent judgments based on stylistic preference\n\n---\n\n## Canonical field rule\n\nThe canonical polish artifact should be treated as using:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n- optional `changes`\n\nOlder field shapes such as:\n- `original`\n- `polished`\n\nshould be treated as legacy/prototype shape and should not remain the architectural target.\n\n---\n\n## Validation layering rule\n\nThe architecture of polish validation is:\n- `tts_polish_output_validator` = per-batch gate\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` = narrow ambiguity arbitration lane\n- `tts_polish_merger` = deterministic composition layer\n- `polish_validator` = whole-polish validation layer\n\nThe whole-polish validator is not a substitute for the earlier batch validation/review path.\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe validator should receive:\n- canonical screenplay scene list or loaded `screenplay.json`\n- canonical merged polish scene list or loaded `tts_polished.json`\n\nBoth layers should be aligned primarily by:\n- `scene_id`\n\nnot by fragile positional `zip` assumptions alone.\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nThe validator should return a structured result containing at minimum:\n- `valid`\n- `eaten_words`\n- `added_words`\n- `acceptable_changes`\n- `dangerous_changes`\n- `affected_scenes`\n- `details`\n\n### Example shape\n```json\n{\n  \"valid\": true,\n  \"eaten_words\": [],\n  \"added_words\": [],\n  \"acceptable_changes\": [],\n  \"dangerous_changes\": [],\n  \"affected_scenes\": [],\n  \"scene_count\": 24,\n  \"details\": \"0 eaten, 0 added, 0 acceptable changes\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Quality expectations\n\nA mature implementation should:\n- align scenes by `scene_id`\n- validate the preservation of original-reference fields explicitly\n- separate obvious deterministic failure from ambiguity already handled upstream\n- avoid being locked to the legacy `original/polished` field shape\n\n---\n\n## Current implementation note\n\nThe current implementation lives in:\n- `runtime/s1/polish_validator.py`\n\nAt the time of this contract, the implementation is functional but still reflects older field assumptions and should be hardened/aligned to the canonical runtime model.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_polish_validator_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 Polish Validator Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the deterministic whole-polish validation layer inside S1._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `polish_validator` validates the canonical merged `tts_polished.json` against the canonical screenplay after approved polish batches have already been merged.\\n\\nIts role is to detect whether the TTS narration layer preserved scene identity, original reference, and semantic safety closely enough for S1 to complete safely.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nThis component sits after:\\n- `tts_polish_output_validator`\\n- optional `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\\n- `tts_polish_merger`\\n\\nAnd before:\\n- `scene_bible_builder`\\n- any supervisor retry decision triggered by polish-level failure\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ownership\\n\\n### Owned by\\n- S1 as a shared deterministic sector component\\n\\n### Not owned by\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- `tts_polish_merger`\\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\\n\\nIt is a whole-artifact validator, not a batch dispatcher and not a semantic reviewer.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Responsibilities\\n\\nThe validator should:\\n- validate scene identity preservation using `scene_id`\\n- validate scene order preservation\\n- validate preservation of `narration_original`\\n- validate presence of `narration_tts`\\n- detect obvious eaten words\\n- detect suspicious additions\\n- expose affected scenes to the supervisor when possible\\n- produce a structured result usable by the supervisor and retry planner\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\nThe validator must **not**:\\n- replace the earlier per-batch polish validation lane\\n- replace semantic review for ambiguous cases\\n- invoke retries\\n- merge batches\\n- invent judgments based on stylistic preference\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical field rule\\n\\nThe canonical polish artifact should be treated as using:\\n- `scene_id`\\n- `narration_original`\\n- `narration_tts`\\n- optional `changes`\\n\\nOlder field shapes such as:\\n- `original`\\n- `polished`\\n\\nshould be treated as legacy/prototype shape and should not remain the architectural target.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Validation layering rule\\n\\nThe architecture of polish validation is:\\n- `tts_polish_output_validator` = per-batch gate\\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` = narrow ambiguity arbitration lane\\n- `tts_polish_merger` = deterministic composition layer\\n- `polish_validator` = whole-polish validation layer\\n\\nThe whole-polish validator is not a substitute for the earlier batch validation/review path.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\nThe validator should receive:\\n- canonical screenplay scene list or loaded `screenplay.json`\\n- canonical merged polish scene list or loaded `tts_polished.json`\\n\\nBoth layers should be aligned primarily by:\\n- `scene_id`\\n\\nnot by fragile positional `zip` assumptions alone.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nThe validator should return a structured result containing at minimum:\\n- `valid`\\n- `eaten_words`\\n- `added_words`\\n- `acceptable_changes`\\n- `dangerous_changes`\\n- `affected_scenes`\\n- `details`\\n\\n### Example shape\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"valid\\\": true,\\n  \\\"eaten_words\\\": [],\\n  \\\"added_words\\\": [],\\n  \\\"acceptable_changes\\\": [],\\n  \\\"dangerous_changes\\\": [],\\n  \\\"affected_scenes\\\": [],\\n  \\\"scene_count\\\": 24,\\n  \\\"details\\\": \\\"0 eaten, 0 added, 0 acceptable changes\\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quality expectations\\n\\nA mature implementation should:\\n- align scenes by `scene_id`\\n- validate the preservation of original-reference fields explicitly\\n- separate obvious deterministic failure from ambiguity already handled upstream\\n- avoid being locked to the legacy `original/polished` field shape\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current implementation note\\n\\nThe current implementation lives in:\\n- `runtime/s1/polish_validator.py`\\n\\nAt the time of this contract, the implementation is functional but still reflects older field assumptions and should be hardened/aligned to the canonical runtime model.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":246,"output":989,"cacheRead":143872,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145107,"cost":{"input":0.0006150000000000001,"output":0.014835000000000001,"cacheRead":0.035968,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.051418000000000005}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774981827364,"responseId":"resp_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc12c43fe08193a30d775b8023b9f8"}}
