{"type":"message","id":"092ec4af","parentId":"f10d6f13","timestamp":"2026-03-31T19:04:48.148Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_wSFwMK7bcY1Yxtmb8lAW4Orp|fc_0f234d88709aef6d0169cc1acf28d8819394dc22ca39597a69","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"5:openclaw agents run stock_video_searcher\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\04_asset_research\\TOOLS.md:16:openclaw agents run asset_advisor\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\05_visual_direction\\TOOLS.md:8:openclaw agents run narrative_segmenter\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\05_visual_direction\\TOOLS.md:65:openclaw agents run asset_matcher\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\05_visual_direction\\TOOLS.md:128:openclaw agents run visual_director\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\06_image_generation\\TOOLS.md:54:openclaw agents run image_qa\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\08_post_production\\TOOLS.md:8:openclaw agents run music_planner\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\08_post_production\\TOOLS.md:50:openclaw agents run sfx_planner\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\08_post_production\\TOOLS.md:91:openclaw agents run lettering_planner\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\tobias\\CONTEXT.md:53:3. Detalhar Production Manager (primeiro sub-agente a criar via `openclaw agents add`)\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\tobias\\MEMORY.md:32:Sub-agentes criados via `openclaw agents add`. Routing por Telegram Topics.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\tobias\\MEMORY.md:73:- [2026-03-25] [DECIS�O] OpenClaw como framework de agentes\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\tobias\\TASKS.md:15:- [ ] Detalhar Production Manager (primeiro sub-agente via `openclaw agents add`)\r\n\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"ember-slug","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\00_CONTEXT.md:81:- Sub-agentes: ~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:7:OpenClaw foi escolhido como framework de agentes. Razoes:\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:6:- **M1**: OpenClaw completo (Gateway + control plane + web UI + agentes)\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:334:| 26 Mar 2026 | Workspace OpenClaw entendido: default em ~/.openclaw/workspace/, sub-agentes em ~/.openclaw/agents/<id>/ |\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md:227:**Localiza��o oficial**: `~/.openclaw/agents/<pm_agent_id>/agent/`\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md:178:**Localiza��o oficial**: `~/.openclaw/agents/<vo_agent_id>/agent/`\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_supervisor_contract.md:28:- **`sm_s1_pre_production` = canonical runtime supervisor**\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_supervisor_contract.md:38:- `sm_s1_pre_production`\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_supervisor_contract.md:98:- `sm_s1_pre_production`\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\implementation\\s1\\01_prototype_v1.md:95:1. OpenClaw configurado com agentes para scene_director e tts_polish\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\implementation\\s1\\01_prototype_v1.md:213:3. Quando OpenClaw estiver pronto: substituir runners por agentes reais\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Advanced Telegram Workflow\\lesson-notes.md:120:- **Self-configuration:** The OpenClaw can modify its own Telegram bot settings when asked, demonstrating the agent's ability to manage its own infrastructure.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:11:When your OpenClaw breaks (stops responding, won't load, config errors), the universal fix is: navigate to your OpenClaw folder in the terminal, open Claude Code (or Codex) inside it, describe the issue with context, and let the coding agent fix the config. This has a reported 100% success rate.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:38:2. Before OpenClaw officially supports it, you ask your agent to switch to the new model\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:139:| \"I can never get it back\" | No. Even in the worst case, copy `memory.md`, `soul.md`, `user.md` into a fresh OpenClaw install and you have the exact same agent. |\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:195:The entire lesson boils down to one simple workflow: **when OpenClaw breaks, use Claude Code (or Codex) to fix it from inside the OpenClaw folder.** The agent's identity, memories, and personality are just markdown files that survive any config corruption. The only thing that breaks is the config, and a coding agent can fix configs trivially. This method has a reported 100% success rate across all types of OpenClaw issues.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\transcription.txt:1:So I want to real quick go over debugging anything that might happen in your OpenClaw. I hear this a lot. My OpenClaw broke. It's not working anymore. I can't talk to my agent. It is a very stress inducing moment. I understand it's happened to me multiple times. You're talking to your OpenClaw. You have to do something. It changes the config and all of a sudden it will not respond anymore. Well I have a fix that has worked with 100% certainty with me. 100% of the issues I've found that are broken OpenClaw, this has fixed it. It is very, very simple. For those that do not know, every single file and folder related to OpenClaw is local on your computer. It lives in the root of your computer, right? So my root is my name here and then inside here is a folder called Claude. This is going to be Claude for you if you did this back in the Claudebot days. If you joined in the OpenClaw days, it'll probably say OpenClaw. This is where every file and folder lives that configures your open claw. By default, it is hidden. It is a hidden folder. So what you're going to need to do is go to your root folder in your finder and then hit command shift period on your keyboard. What that'll do is reveal all the hidden files and folders revealing your open claw folder. This is where your memories live, your persona, your soul, all of that lives inside there. All the config files are inside this folder. Now when you have your OpenClaw do something like change its model or change its config if it breaks something or does something wrong the entire thing stops working So we need to fix whatever broken your config file Most of the time this happens when you switching models So a lot of times anthropic will come out with a new model, sonnet four, six, opus four, six, whatever. And before open claw officially supports it, you go and you try to make it. So it uses that new model, which is totally fine. I do it. I do it all the time. The issue is sometimes OpenClaw changes its config file wrong and breaks itself. It will try to go to the new model and it will just do it wrong and it breaks itself and you can't talk to it anymore. So here's what you need to do when something like this happens, when your OpenClaw is no longer responding or really any other problem you're running into when it comes to OpenClaw and it's not working correctly. First thing you do is take a deep breath because I understand how stressful and anxious it can make you when things break. When your best friend stops talking to you, I get it. Take a deep breath. Then what you want to do is open up your terminal. So you go in here. What you want to do in your terminal is find that clawed folder, right? So you want to go into that folder. So if you type LS and hit enter, it will list every file and folder of the folder you're inside of. Typically you start off at the root folder here. If you see your open claw folder, whether it's clawed or open claw, what you want to do is you want to CD into it. CD-ing into it basically makes you go into that folder in your terminal. So you can do CD, then you start typing the name of whatever it is, OpenClaw or Claude. You can hit tab to autocomplete and then you hit enter and it goes into your folder and now you can see you know your name of your computer and then Claude or OpenClaude will be the next thing there That means you in the folder If you hit LS, you can see everything that's in that folder. So first, get to the root folder. You can do this by doing, you know, typically if this is your first time in a terminal, it'll have you in the root folder. But if you're deeper in, all you need to do is do CD space dot dot that backs you up, that takes you a level higher in the hierarchy. doing that until you go to the root. And then once you're in the root CD into the open claw folder, right? Boom. We're in here now, right? You can see the computer and the name of the folder. Now, what we're going to do is go into Claude code. So either Claude code or Codex, whichever one you're subscribed to. So you're going to type in Claude, C-L-A-U-D-E for Claude code or Codex for Codex. And that will open up Claude code or Codex in your open claw folder. So either one works they're both going to work well now and now you have a coding agent a very smart coding agent that is going to fix your issue so whatever your issue is you go hey you're in my open claw folder I'm having this issue dot dot dot then you describe your issue it's not responding anymore give it context to say I was trying to switch the model I was trying to change this I went in and I tried to change the config file myself whatever it is you list that out then you hit enter and ClaudeCode will fix it. It has fixed it with 100% success rate for me. 100% success rate this has worked, right? So you just describe whatever it is, ClaudeCode will go research OpenClaw on the internet understand how it works and then go in and figure out what you did wrong and fix it for you This should make it work There is no way to break this other than messing with a config file, and config files are easily fixable. Breaking your OpenClaw does not delete it, does not ruin your memories, does not make it so you'll never get it back again. Your agent is not dead because everything lives in your folder, right? In that OpenClaw folder. So you see memory.md, You see user.md. You see soul.md. Those don't break when your OpenClaw stops working. That's just a markdown file that describes everything. That's all your OpenClaw is. Your config just broke and it will fix the config and you'll be right back to normal. Even if somehow the whole thing was permanently broken, it doesn't matter. You can just copy your memory.md file, your soul.md file, put it in a new OpenClaw. It'll be the exact same agent, the exact same OpenClaw. So I promise you, you'll be all right. This should work with basically 100% certainty. If this doesn't work, feel free to post in the community and we'll try to fix it for you. But this should work pretty much every time. I mean I have messed with everything, broken everything, and this has fixed it every single time. Make sure you give it enough context and CloudCode or Codex should be able to fix it. If you're not familiar with CloudCode or don't have it installed, I have an entire CloudCode masterclass. You should take that. It's awesome. Everyone should learn how to use CloudCode. There's so much value in it. still with open claw. There's so much value from learning clawed code. So make sure to take that as well. If you haven't, and I will see you in the next video.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Local Models\\transcription.txt:1:Local AI is a very important topic because I believe this is the future of OpenClaw. Everyone running their own local models, powering their own AI agent. And so I think this is very important to learn, especially early on before this has even gotten big and before many people are doing it. Because if you can learn this now, you can get ahead of the trends and you can unlock power with OpenClaw that most people do not have, which will give you an advantage. you an advantage. Now what are local AI models? Local AI models are just models that run on your computer. So whatever computer have models that run on it could be your computer, could be your iPhone, could be any device you have. Local models can run on them. Basically the way things work now is when you send a prompt to chat GPT or to Claude, it sends your prompt to the internet, to the servers that Claude or chat GPT are running on. A bunch of calculations are ran on those servers and then the response is sent back to you, right? So it's not happening locally, it's happening in the cloud. There are some disadvantages to that. Speed being one of them, privacy being another, all your prompts and all your responses are being saved on servers in the cloud so people who work for those companies can see what you're saying. Costs being another, you pay for every single token. So every single prompt you send and every single response you get back, that costs you money. It's basically like a toll boot. But when you run your models locally, instead of all those calculations happening on the cloud, on someone else's server, they're instead happening on your own devices, on your phone, on your computer, whatever it is. There are many advantages to this. One is it's completely free. If you're doing the calculations on your own computer, you're not paying for someone else to do the calculations, right? So it's completely free other than the cost of energy, right? Other than the cost of the power going into your computer. It's completely private. So the prompts you send, the responses you get, they stay on your computer. You don't even need to be connected to the internet to run these models It completely private and secure It unlimited 24 So the fact that it free unlocks all these new use cases that allow you to run models 24 365 right If you not paying for tokens, you can just have your AI calculating and doing things for you at all hours of the day, which is a big advantage. And lastly, education. You're learning a ton about AI by loading them locally, using them locally, seeing how they work. Just from an education perspective of learning how AI works, that's a massive advantage. A big one too I don't have here is just they can't change the models, they can't make them stupider, you're completely sovereign, they can't kick you off, they can't take it away from you, it's your model, it can never be taken away. It's like the bitcoin of AI models where you own your model, no one can change it, no one can take it away from you and those are some really big advantages. Now how do you run it? There's many different ways to do it. You can do it on Mac studios, Mac studios have a ton of memory, memory is the big thing here because when you load local AI models they get loaded into memory and so Macs have a really nice architecture where you get a ton of memory. Then you have Nvidia chips. Nvidia chips are really good and have their own advantages. They're really really fast, much faster than Mac but you don't get as much memory with them so you can't load quite as big models. So Mac devices you can load much bigger smarter models they're just a bit slower. Nvidia chips you run smaller models but they're much faster. On top of that you get some advantages to Nvidia where you can also fine-tune and train your own models so if that's something you're looking to do as well Nvidia chips are the way to go for that but those are your two options. I have both. I have a couple Mac studios and I have a DGX Spark which is what you see here. DGX Spark is probably the most popular way to run local models with Nvidia chips just because it's it's very much like a Mac where you don't have to kind of build your own computer you just buy one device plug it and it just works right away. So you want to decide what you want to do. If you just want to load local models and use them, Mac might be the way to go if speed not too important for you If you want to get like super advanced fine tune your own models train your own models then you might want to consider an NVIDIA device The more memory you get with each the bigger the models you can run right So if you get a Mac Studio, you know, you can get away with getting a 64 gig or 128 gig Mac Studio and run really, really good models. I have a 512 gig just because I'm crazy and I want the maximum power available to me. But you can get away with 64 or 128 if you want to run really powerful models. Now listen, you can go even smaller than that if you want. If you want to go 32 gigabyte, you can do that. You're just gonna be loading smaller models, right? They're not gonna be quite as smart. They're not gonna be able to handle quite as complex challenges or tasks, but that's fine. You know, there's nothing wrong with that and I think over time as we go, smarter models will fit with smaller footprints. You'll be able to run better and better models as time goes on. Now which models can you run? There's so many different models. If you're debating which one you can run, go to your OpenClaw and say, here's how much memory I have. Here's the device I have. Which models can I run with this hardware that I have? And your OpenClaw will be able to tell you. Again, if you don't have a ton of memory, you're not going to be able to run as smart models. But even if you can run a dumb model, there's still going to be advantages to that, right? The way I like to think about it is right now as of recording, you're still probably going to want to use cloud models. So Chad GPT or Claude as your orchestrator, as your high level brain of your open claw. But what you can do is you can start replacing muscles with local models. For instance, I use Quen 3.5 for coding. For a lot of my coding, I use Quen 3.5. That's a local model I'm running on my Mac Studio. Now, if you're running a much smaller device with only a little bit of memory, maybe you don't replace coding. Maybe you still use a cloud model for code for coding, but you use the local model for scraping online finding data online doing research online, right? So depending on your device, you can do much bigger tasks much bigger muscles with local models like coding But if you only have like 32 gigabytes or smaller Maybe you only do writing your research with the local models because that a lot less compute intensive So how do you set this up Your OpenClaw can pretty much handle it all for you OpenClaw did it for me I said hey load Quen It found the right website to go to, found the right model, loaded it on my computer. A really easy way to do this if you want a visual editor is LM Studio. It's completely free. You can download it and you can search for models there and you can see what modelers are available. Download them and load them very easily. If you ever get confused along the way, you can just ask your open claw how to do it and it will handle it for you. But I think local models are the future. I see a future where everyone - it's not even just the orchestrator that's cloud. You're going to have local models doing everything and not a single piece of your AI stack will be going to the cloud. And you'll be basically a sovereign individual that no one can take their super intelligence away from. I think this is something that's important to experiment with now. I'm experimenting with it now. I have a bunch of Mac studios and a DJX Spark. You don't need all that. Again, you can even have a Mac mini and run local models. It will be genius level. Probably not, but you can start offloading some of your tasks, which will save you money and also just educate you on the technology. So those are local models. I hope this is helpful. Let me know if you have any questions on this. I think it's worth everyone experimenting with. I think you'll be ahead of the pack, ahead of the group, especially if you can start setting up some more advanced use cases, Just as an example of an advanced use case, I have Quen 3.5, which is my local model, every 20 minutes going online and reading Reddit and X for challenges people have so that I can build out apps to solve those challenges. That's something you wouldn't be able to do with a cloud model because it'd be really expensive running ChatGPT every 20 minutes and searching the web for you. It would just get really expensive. But because I have local models, I can just continuously run this over and over and over and over again and not have to worry about costs. Those are the types of advanced use cases and workflows that unlock with local models. So you want to be taking advantage of them. Hope it was helpful. I'll see you in the next module.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:12:Mission Control is a fully custom web dashboard built and maintained by your OpenClaw agent. It serves as a centralized hub for all custom tooling, applications, analytics, and workflows. The key insight: you do not need to code anything yourself -- your OpenClaw builds and maintains the entire dashboard via natural language prompts.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:19:- Built entirely from scratch by your OpenClaw agent (not a pre-made template).\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:193:The next video covers **Mission Statement** -- why every OpenClaw should have one, how to create yours, and how it improves everything the agent does. The mission statement is displayed at the top of the Mission Control dashboard.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\transcription.txt:1:So for this video, I want to go through mission control. I want to go over what mission control is, why it's so important. I'm going to go through mine in detail and then I will show you how to build your own. Mission control is a super important concept when it comes to OpenClaw. This is where you build out your custom tooling for OpenClaw. OpenClaw is just a kind of thin wrapper around an AI model. It basically gives your AI model a rule set, a personality, and the ability to schedule different tasks. This is both a strength and a weakness. The strength is this makes it fully customizable. The weakness is if you're not too technical, it might be hard to get the full power out of OpenClaw. The good news is I will show you how to get the full power out right here. So Mission Control is basically your fully custom dashboard where you can generate any tools, applications, dashboards, videos, analytics, anything you need to get the most out of your OpenClaw. It is completely custom, completely built from scratch and allows you to build any tool out you need the moment you need it. So what I'm about to show you is completely built and maintained by my OpenClaw. When you go through this, you'll be doing the same thing. You'll be having your OpenClaw build out these tools too. You don't need to code. You're not not even vibe coding. It's your open claw that's doing the vibe coding here. And this is going to be super powerful because the moment you need a tool, the moment you want to create a system, the moment you want to get insight into some sort of piece of data or analysis, you will be able to build the tool quickly right inside your mission control. So let me give you some examples of what I got here. This is my mission control. All the tools I'm about to show you are completely custom built. Starting with the task screen, these are all the tasks my open claw is working on at the moment as they do the task, they move it along this task board. And it just gives me insight into what my open claw is doing. I also have a content board. This is a content pipeline. This is basically another Kanban board where I can put in ideas for content. I could, I could flush it out and put in my ideas, put in scripts, put in what platform it's on, put it, give it a priority. And I could also say, Henry, write me a script and hit a button in my open claw. We'll go and write an entire script based on my idea. So it's a fully automated and custom content pipeline I have built out. I have a calendar. So this is where I can see what tasks my OpenClaw has scheduled. So obviously a big part about OpenClaw is that it can do tasks on its own. That schedules its own tasks. I wanted visibility into what my OpenClaw was doing. I wanted to see what it had scheduled. So I said hey OpenClaw Henry build me a calendar that shows me all your scheduled tasks right Because I would ask it to do things like hey write me a newsletter and say all right boss I got it scheduled but I wouldn know for sure I wanted visual confirmation that he actually scheduled it So now with my calendar I actually can see what it has scheduled. And after I go through each one of these tools that I have built out, I'll go through which one of these are critical for you. Then I'll go through how to build it out and then how to figure out which tools you actually want to build based on your own workflows. I have a memory section. This shows me every memory my open claw has. So one of the strengths about OpenClaw is its memory system, right? It remembers so many things. Every conversation you have with it, it remembers something from it. I wanted insight into what's in its memory system. So I said, hey, make a tool where I can read all your memories easily. And it built that for me. Now I can go in and see every single memory from every single day, everything we talked about, everything I wanted to remember. It's super easy. I can even search it. So if I want to see everything about Mac Studios in its memory, I can search for that and that will come up in here. I have a document section, right? So a big part of my workflow with Henry is it builds out entire documents based on conversation. So maybe I'll say something like, hey, look into this new technology. It'll look into it. Then I'll say, hey, create me an architecture document that goes over how I can implement that with you. And it'll build me these documents. The issue was these documents were stored in different folders scattered across my computer. I wanted to make it super easy to view these documents in my browser. And so it built this docs tool where now I can go in and see every single doc makes it super easy I can search through them again And if I want to see any docs that's made on Mac studios I can search through it and I can see every single document is made that mentions Mac studios. This is a fun one This is the office. It gives me insight into every single agent. I have working in what they're doing It's just a cool visual. There's nothing too crazy about it It just shows me what my agents are doing at any given time. I think it's fun big part of this is fun You're allowed to have fun when using Open Claw and everything has to be a hyper optimized workflow. Sometimes you can just have a little fun. That's why I did this. I have the team screen, which again shows me all my agents, shows me their roles and responsibilities. This has some functionality. This is basically context given to Henry. So he knows which agent to give different tasks to. And this just allows me to stay on top of who my agents are and what they got. And then I have more custom tooling. So this is a feedback dashboard. This shows me feedback people have submitted on my SaaS creator buddy So this doesn't just have to be workflows with your AI agent This could also be custom workflows with other things you're doing and then if I want I can click this build this button on any of these features And Henry will go and actually build out that feature and implement it into creator buddy So a lot of really cool advanced workflows I set up here So how do I get this built out What the process Well it really really simple This can all be done with a single prompt You go into your chat with your open claw and you say something like I want to build a mission control This will be a place for us to build out our own custom tooling. Please build this in next JS for me. Next JS is a framework for web apps that is super easy to use. All AI's know how to build in it. You take this, you can pause right here, put this into your own open claw right now and it will build it out for you. Then it will start the web server and you can actually see your mission control from there. Anytime you're doing something and you think of a custom tool you can use for it. I just go in and say, okay, please build a docs viewer in our mission control that shows all our docs. Boom, hit enter. It just builds it out for me. It does the vibe coding for me. I don't need to know how to code. It just does it. The mindset I like to have around this is anytime I use any sort of app. So for instance, I was like saving my video ideas to my notion and I'm like, why am I using notion for this when I can just build my own custom tool with Henry? And I went in there and I'm like, Hey, build me a content pipeline. And now I have that in my mission control and I don't need to use other tools. It's centralizing everything I need in this one piece of software for me, which is really sick. That's the mindset you need to have and that you'll develop as you build this out is, okay, what can I build to make my workflows easier? But I got good news for you. You don't even need to develop that mindset as much if you do enough reverse prompting. So a really good way to do this after you put in that initial prompt of building out your mission control is you can reverse prompt. So you can go in and you can say, based on what you know about me, what are some tools we can build out in our mission control to improve our workflows, right? Simple pause here, grab that, put that inside of your open claw. It will give you a list of tools you can build out and you just select one and it builds it for you and adds it to your mission control. Easy. Within five minutes, you have custom tools that have improved your workflow. The number one request I get a ton is, Hey, open source, your mission control, open source, your mission control. I'm going to do it. This is still a work in progress. I don't want to open source something that's a work in progress because that will only confuse you guys more. But here's the thing. I don't think you should be using my open source mission control anyway. I think it's hyper critical that you actually build out your own mission control. I think all the tools should be custom to you. I don't think you should be copying me because just taking my tools doesn't do any good for you. You want tools completely custom to your own workflows. Your workflows might not be like my workflows. So what I would do if I was you is I go in get your mission control set up right you just go to your open closet hey building a mission control where we can build custom tooling And then you sit there and for half an hour you do an exercise where you reverse prompt What tools can we build out Let's talk about my workflows. What can improve this workflow? You get yourself four to five tools built out based on what you do with your open claw regularly. If you haven't done too much with your open claw up to this point, good news. Go to your open claw, say, Hey, this is what I do. These are my tasks every day. This is what I'm focused on. What tools can we build out in our mission control based on that? Again, reverse prompting. And then you can get those tools built out for you. And it's always a work in progress. You should always be tinkering with this. You should always be adding new tools, improving the tools you have, deleting old tools. I've deleted like 15 different tools from this side where in the moment it feels like it's a good thing to have. And then I realize I don't use it for like an entire week. And I'm like, all right, this is pointless. Let's just get rid of it. You should be doing the same thing, constantly adding new tools, constantly removing tools, constantly tinkering and building. Again, if you just have fun with this, play around, experiment, that's going to be the best way to make the most impactful mission control possible. If I were to give recommendations on tools to begin with, I definitely think that you want a calendar tool to see what schedule tasks you have with your OpenClaw. I definitely think you should have a memory tool so you can view your memories in here. A docs tool might be the most important one so you can see all the docs it's created. And then I'd also create a team one if you're using multiple agents. If you're not, then forget about it. That's more advanced stuff and we'll get into that eventually. But those are probably the most important ones. What I'm going to go through in the next video is actually what I have up here, which is my mission statement. I think every open clause should have a mission statement. And what I'm going to do is tell you why that's important, how to get your own, and how it's going to improve everything you do. But that is the mission control. That's how to set up. Feel free to pause right now and spend some time first setting up the base and template of your mission control. Then you can go in and start reverse prompting and getting the tools built out. If you like the way mine looks, just as a hint, I said, make my mission control look like linear. I want the simplicity and cleanliness of linear. Linear is like a project management app that I think looks really nice and clean. And so it just took inspiration from that and made what you see here. I think this looks really nice. So feel free to steal that from me as well. Go to your OpenClaw after you've built it out and say, hey, make the styling look more like linear. And you should get a clean looking mission control like what you see here. As you build out your mission control, feel free to go into the community and say what tools you're putting in and share what you've built. It's so much fun. This is one of the most fun parts about OpenClaw, just building cool things out and tinkering and experimenting. Hope this was helpful. See you in the next module.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Statement\\transcription.txt:1:The next concept I want to go over is a mission statement. It's something you see right here at the top of my mission control. My mission statement is an autonomous organization of AI agents that do work for me and produce value 24-7. This is what I'm trying to build. This is my north star for everything I do at my OpenClaw. I want to build an autonomous business that is constantly producing value. I know if I can do that, I'd probably be the first person in the entire world to do it. and it would help my content and all my businesses a ton. So that is what my kind of North Star metric for everything I build with OpenClaw is. Having a mission statement is really critical, in my opinion, for many different reasons. It kind of focuses the energy on your OpenClaw a ton. I think a challenge a lot of people have with AI is they don't really know what to do with it on a day-to-day basis. They don't really know what tasks to give it. They kind of use it like a glorified search engine. the mission statement gives your AI a little bit more focus and constantly pushes it forward. And what I mean by that is every time I ask a question, every time I give Henry a task, it keeps this mission statement in mind and make sure everything it does pushes us closer to that vision we are trying to build out This also makes reverse prompting a lot more powerful because for instance when I sit down and my AI is idle I'm able just to say, hey, based on our mission statement and everything we've done so far, what is one task we can do right now that will get us closer to this mission statement? And what that will do is allow Henry to come up with tasks on its own to get us closer to that goal. As your AI gets more autonomous, this becomes really important because then it's able to come up with its own tasks that get you closer to the goals you're looking for. You're giving it a North Star, which makes all its tasks it does a lot more powerful. As you build more trust with your Open Claw and you start having you do work at night autonomously, so for instance, if you say, hey, every night at 3 a.m. do three tasks that advance what we're doing, having a mission statement gets those tasks a lot more useful for you. So here's what you need to do. You need a mission statement at the top of your mission control. The reason why I have it printed at the top of my mission control is it puts it in writing, right? Henry is always in our mission control, so it's always going to see this mission statement. It makes it very hard for your AI to forget what your mission statement is when you have it written out in something you constantly working in So I have it at the top of my mission control You want to do the same thing You have two options here You can come up with your mission statement Maybe that obvious to you Maybe you already know what you working for with your open claw or maybe you don Maybe you're not quite sure. You're just tinkering with open claw and you know it's powerful, but you don't know which direction to go with it. That's totally fine as well. Your other option here is the same solution I give for almost every challenge with open claw, reverse prompting. based on what you know about me, what would be a good mission statement that would make us very successful? If your open claw doesn't know much about you, then go, Hey, here are all my goals and ambitions. Here's everything about me. Here's everything about my career based on all of this. What would be a good mission statement for us to constantly be looking at and striving towards? Even if you know your mission statement, it probably is a good exercise to go in reverse prompt and kind of validate that you have the right mission statement. But once you get that mission statement built out and put into your mission control, you want to make sure that every day you go, you sit down and you go, what can we do today to get closer to our mission statement? And every time I do this, invariably, my AI comes up with something helpful to build or do or advance our system in some sort of way. So I think a mission statement is hypercritical. This is a perfect opportunity for you to pause to reverse prompt your AI a little bit come up with this mission statement And then once you do that get it in your mission control and then sit there and come up with several tasks with your AI through reverse prompting that it can do to get you closer to that mission statement This has led me to building multiple tools in my mission control that's made my AI more autonomous. This has caused me to build out entire systems for automating all my agents and getting them to do things on their own. So a lot of good has come out of this and I'm sure a lot of good will come out of this for you. So take a second. Now that you have your mission control set up, get a mission statement in there. If you don't know yours reverse prompts. And then once you've done that reverse prompts again, to start getting your AI to build out tasks that get you close to that mission statement. This is a core piece of my open claw workflow. So get that done. And in the next video, I'm going to go over making your AI a lot more proactive, having it scheduled tasks and things like that. And I will see you in the next module. Thank you.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\OpenClaw mindset you need to have\\lesson-notes.md:19:**Concept:** OpenClaw is not a chatbot you prompt step-by-step. It's an autonomous agent that knows more than you about most things and can move faster. Your job is to be a manager, not a micromanager.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Vibe Coding in OpenClaw\\lesson-notes.md:23:2. **Mission control / internal tooling** -- When building tools that OpenClaw uses for itself (agent management tools, organization tools, productivity tools). OpenClaw knows its own mission control best, so it's the ideal builder for its own ecosystem. Just tell it: \"put this tool in our mission control.\"\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Vibe Coding in OpenClaw\\transcription.txt:33:[01:36 - 01:42] OpenClaw uses for itself, whether it's different agent management tools or organization tools or\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\What is OpenClaw_\\lesson-notes.md:18:- OpenClaw is not a chatbot you go back and forth with. It is an **AI agent that controls your computer** and takes autonomous action.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\What is OpenClaw_\\lesson-notes.md:63:| **OpenClaw / ClaudeBot** | The core AI agent system being taught |\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\AutomatedSEOLesson\\transcription.txt:1:Hey guys, OpenClaw SEO Content Automation, a complete guide. I was working on this and then I realized I could do it better. So I actually rebuilt it for myself and I'm giving you some results in here, which I'm doing, and you can kind of follow along to do this for you. So yeah, awesome. So SEO Content Automation. All right, let's run through it. So this is big. I mean, this is actually a 51-page document. So I'm not going to read every word. I'm going to give it to you, and you guys can go through this and get it set up in your account. So here's what we're going to do. We're going to talk about what it does. We're going to talk about the prerequisites. I don't know why the system formatted it all like this. Quick start, how to get started, trend discovery, keyword, content creation, publishing automation, orchestrator setup monitoring and optimization troubleshooting and some advanced strategies I put in so in this guide I'm gonna show you how to build a fully autonomous SEO system using open claw so 24 7 here's some my costs in running this for some of our clients and it's really cool so let's go through the workflow so every six hours it's going to look for new trending topics and Then daily, it's going to validate keywords and do a competition check. Then it's going to write a couple of optimized articles between 1,500 and 2,000 words. It's going to publish to WordPress or wherever you want to post to. And it's going to track performance. It's going to self-optimize. This is one of the pieces that I'm really trying to put into my systems that I'm putting together now. is because when I work with AI and I'm developing something, I always tell it that it's stupid and that that's wrong. And I'm always trying to correct it, right? And I'm like, that feedback loop, that feedback loop needs to be in the process because it's basically machine learning. If it could learn from its own feedback loop to see what the results are, what the keywords that are performing, what is landing, what's not landing. It can analyze that and then it can self-heal and self-optimize to make it better. Because using OpenClaw over the past month, one of the things I found is that if I'm totally hands-off in the AI process, then what happens is I don't get to tell it it's wrong. So it's doing stupid stuff and it's been really frustrating. It doesn't matter the context I give it. It's still making bad decisions because it's making decisions, not me. The person with 25 years experience of blogging I know what good and what not good So if I trying to train it and I mean this is another piece that I want to build my local LLM and load it up with my entire knowledge base and train it because when I just give it a little context file and then it goes off and uses Claude or whatever, it's making bad decisions. It is so frustrating. So this is something I'm trying to add into everything going forward is the self-optimizing piece because that's going to be essential to understand how its piece is performing and get it to learn what about that piece is making it perform and make your future pieces better. So maybe that was a little sidebar, but I wanted to bring that So Brave Search API, I think it's like four bucks a month for like two million queries. So start on the free tier, build this out once it starts working, four bucks a month, you're searching the internet. Like it's so cheap. So the easiest way to get up and going. I don't like the whole browser piece and the headless browser and the Chromium and all the other different solutions out there. I don't really like that. I like the Brave Search API. It just makes it so much easier because it's not going to hit blocks, and it's so much easier to do this. Now, Reddit, you can use Reddit to feed in information and so forth. You can use that. Here's your WordPress site. Here's your OpenClaw setup. We're going to talk about that, and we're going to talk about news APIs. So this is one source that you can use, and also Google Search Console. and if you want to, this is optional. I'll put optional. Optional, optional, cool. Optional, you don't need to do that. Like you can just have it set a cron that it will post for you every so often and it'll just do it on the cron. So like this is optional, you don't really need that. Okay, so again, I'm not gonna read everything. You're gonna make a directory, you're gonna set up API keys, you're gonna do your niches and then you're going to set up your API keys here for OpenClaw. You're going to set up, you're going to connect, you're going to test, you're going to make sure it's working. Great. So now we're looking for trends. So here's where you have to start defining some of those trends and some of the pieces that you're looking for. So you'll have to put in your niche here, here, here, what it is you're looking for, finding emerging things that are being talked about or breaking news or whatever it is that you want to talk about. Boom, done. You'll do that. So now you have the OAuth running, you're able to do that. You're able to search Reddit, search what people are talking about, you know, find those different opportunities. Here's the news API where you can go and grab things there. You can cross reference with different sites. You can do you know freshness score and you know set up some trends and things like that Set some criteria of what it looking for Boom done Like that the entire prompt that you can add in This explains what it does This explains the expected output of what you're trying to accomplish. Here's the keyword research. I'm realizing that this is going to be really long if I go through everything line by line. So that's everything. You'll have to customize this for your topic here, here, here. So you'll have to feed that in. Moving along. So yeah, I tried to be pretty thorough on this because I did it the first time. It really wasn't working very well. So I made some improvements to it. And that's why I made this video a little bit later than what I was posting on Instagram about. So yeah, here's a complete prompt here for how to write those articles. So it'll give you a step-by-step on exactly how to write those articles. I try to be thorough. So, I mean, that's a pretty good prompt. Pretty well laid out, pretty well articulated, so forth. So, ready? Good. Publish. Cool. So, publishing automation. So, again, gave me a prompt for that. It gives you step-by-step on exactly what to do. It'll check to make sure things aren't spelled wrong and things aren't, you know, there's, you know, proper grammar and so forth. So really good prompt there as well in order for the publishing bot to do what it is it needs to do. Okay. Here is the master orchestrator setup. So now you're going to have the orchestration to say, you know, run a complete SEO content system autonomously. And when it gets done, like this is a phase, this is what you're going to need to do. Go ahead and run this. So this will set up the project to run autonomously. And so again, step by step. Final notes, it's going to run 24-7, minimal intervention. This thing is just going to run and it's just going to do its thing. Because, I mean, let's face it, that's what we sign up to use OpenClaw for, is for it to run autonomously, right? So give it a max of the tokens it can use per month. Again, go and do the token calibration before you do this, because as you do that, this will be dialed in a little bit more. So it's not going to burn excess tokens. and therefore you can keep your budget a little bit lower in order to have this orchestrate and run for you and do that. Otherwise, you're going to be burning tokens and so forth. Also, my multi-agent is running this. So if you haven't gone through the multi-agent setup yet, go through that and make sure you have that working because that's really going to help with... Haiku is going to go out and scrape and find information. Sana is going to be writing for you in the background. Everything orchestrates really well. It's being passed back and forth between multiple agents. And, you know, it's doing things very optimally for you where you're not burning a bunch of cash on Sonic to do this. Right. So here's some troubleshooting steps. So a couple of issues you might run into a couple of issues I ran into that you might run into as well And here how to solve some of those issues and some of those blocks So yeah here some advanced strategies So you can build some topic clusters So you could do like, you know, a main thread. And then you could have a couple of topics underneath that. Like for me, I could do OpenClaw as one. And I could do, you know, Claude Code as another topic. 