t_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.txt:13:OpenClaw skills are modular folders that teach your AI agent how to use tools, APIs, and workflows. Each skill is built around a SKILL.md file containing YAML metadata and markdown instructions. They follow the open AgentSkills specification, which means they're portable across any agent platform that supports the format (including OpenAI Codex).\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.txt:264:1Password: \"From Magic to Malware\" - 1password.com/blog/from-magic-to-malware-how-openclaws-agent-skills-become-an-attack-surface\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.txt:269:Kaspersky: \"New OpenClaw AI Agent Found Unsafe\" - kaspersky.com/blog/openclaw-vulnerabilities-exposed\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\transcription.txt:1:All right, in this video, let's talk about installing skills. Let me zoom in a little bit and let's go through this. Let's talk about this. So OpenClaw skills, just to be totally transparent, you don't have to install a single skill. My agent right now that's running, zero skills. Like I made the skills. So you don't need to install somebody else's code. and somebody else's skills that come from either OpenClaw itself that are built in, that you can go to the web agent, go to skills, toggle them on, it'll install and use it, and you can configure it. So that's one way to install skills. The other way is going to platforms like Clawhub, which OpenClaw does recognize Clawhub as a place to get skills, but all the skills in Clawhub, I have it up here, are uploaded by users. So you can come here and you can upload your own skills. So, yeah, like it's like Napster and LimeWire all over again, right, where we're all infecting each other's computers with different stuff. Right. I mean, I guess we're going backwards to go forwards. So as of February 2026, security researchers, I have the article below this as well, that I did some research on it, found 341 malicious skills in Clawhub and 283 of those skills, 7% had critical credential exposure. So yeah, that's something to talk about. Like we're making our OpenClaw less safe by installing the skills that are coming from Claw Hub. So just something to throw out there and we can talk about this. So what are skills? Each skill is built around skill.md file and it has some metadata and it's got markdown instructions. It might overwrite some of your other context files as well. We can talk about that like this one. I hit it up a second ago. By downloaded, top downloads. What am I doing? Newest. I had it up like literally a second ago Installs right Right Where it go I don know I find it Not highlighted Sort by download. Jesus. All right. So improving agent. So they have this scan security. This one is seen as benign, so self-improving agent, but you can literally make it self-improve itself. So yeah, you'll download here and then you'll be able to install it. But you can like download it and not install it and just kind of understand like the file structure and what it is it's doing. And, you know, it's kind of giving it here so you can manually do these things without installing this whole skill. So that's something I want to mention is it's just editing some of those context files. So we can do that without downloading these, you know, scripts from other people. OK, cool. So there's currently 5700 community built skills. And as you saw, I was kind of messing with that toggle to toggle. You can toggle by how many have been downloaded. So you got installs here and then you can toggle them by downloads. You can toggle those