u might want to run a B-roll task, put it into the file, name that folder B-roll, and then it can call up that B-roll to use it at a later date. So you might want to do that. You might want to have your agent, you know, create some B-roll. So it's not creating B-roll in the workflow every single time. It would be pulling from that folder. So just something. So then you assemble it, caption it, put the pieces together, post-production, you can have it run through polishing. And then this is something that I'm probably not going to do, but let me know if you guys do this. It's just, um, I'm not going to automate posting to platforms. Um, you know, each platform has their own rate limits and has their own restrictions and their posting criteria and they're constantly changing APIs. So if they change their API, then you need to change it in your system. So I'm not going to do this, but I'm going to save everything in a project folder. And then from there I can schedule it out using one of the scheduling softwares or something like that. Maybe a later video I'll do is how to have a workflow to schedule into, I'll look at buffer and a couple of those other platforms, but yeah, so this is a point. If you do want to do this, let me know how it goes. If you don't do it, maybe not do this to automatically schedule because it could step on itself and create rate limit issues. And, um, you know, there, there are a lot of issues with the APIs on the platforms for each one of these platforms. And I just don't want to mess with them and I don't want to get banned and I don't want you guys to get banned either. So yeah, definitely, um, you know, be careful with this one. I'll make a note. Be careful with auto posting just as a note. All right. So scheduling batch cost optimization, make sure that you're, um, you know, using the multi-tiered agents. You're not just using Opus for something like this. Be sure to use the principle, the 85, 15% with Sonnet. You can use Haiku for a lot of this and have it manage a lot of these calls for you and then have Sonnet doing the polishing for you. Um, again, I like Sonnet writing for me. So, yeah, like haiku can start it and sonnet can finish it. But I have, um, you know, a lot of sonnet when it comes to writing because the writing is much better and I'm willing to pay a little bit higher end on my content. So yeah. So yeah, that's a step-by-step, you know, scaling from one to a hundred. I want to see you guys build this out. I want to see you walk this through. Here's some real world playbooks on, you know, maybe some clients you could go win, or if you are in these spaces, you can run these playbooks and so forth. So that's a UGC machine. again in the next video i'm going to do a vo 3.1 integration with my open claw because that is how i'm going to do mine and um that absolutely like that is my system i think it's so photorealistic and it's perfect but if you want to try to program these a couple of different ways and you know see how it works for you definitely let us know in the community so i'll get this posted up\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:121:Building an ML Ops system in OpenClaw requires a different way of thinking about your agents. Before you write a single workflow, you need to answer four questions:\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:132:highest-volume OpenClaw agent. These answers will drive every architectural decision in the\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:607:The Action Logger operates as a post-task webhook action in OpenClaw, not a conversational agent. Configure it as follows:\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:1061:and the current system prompt for an OpenClaw agent. Your job is to produce\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:1591:Cold outreach is the highest-ROI application of OpenClaw ML Ops. The performance ceiling for a non-ML outreach agent is typically 3-8% reply rate. An ML Ops outreach engine, after 90 days of loop operation, consistently achieves 12-25% reply rates in most B2B markets. Here is the complete deployment blueprint.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MachineLearningSkillLesson\\OpenClaw_ML_Ops_Guide.docx.txt:1818:This chapter contains every system prompt in the OpenClaw ML Ops system in final, deployable form. Each prompt is labeled with its agent role, trigger condition, recommended model, and key variables it expects. Copy these directly into OpenClaw - they are written to work without modification for most use cases.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MACvsVPSvsPCLesson\\transcription.txt:1:Okay, so the question came up, which platform to use, Mac, PC, virtual private system, which is best? Let's talk about the use cases for each one and drill down to this, so make that bigger. Okay, so I run on Mac. I also have a PC here. It's like my gaming computer. I didn't want to use it on there even though I have like a really good card, you know, 50, 90 or whatever I have. I don't know, whatever I have in there. And I didn't want to use it. I didn't want to use that machine. I didn't want to have multiple things. So I decided the Mac was best for me. Now I am deploying on virtual systems, virtual machines, and I'm doing it for SaaS use cases. So the key thing is first define what your use case is and what you want to do and where you see yourself going. So I did a quick comparison mix. So best for solo dev testing, workflows, et cetera. budget build. So you can build cheaper, you can run cheaper on that. And then VPS, production, uptime, client deployment, scaling, going to market, SaaS, yada, yada, yada. So I'm working on taking OpenClaw and putting it into its own social agent that I can put restrictions on it and then allow for users to be able to download my software as a service, which is really just running OpenClaw on the back end, that's gonna be VPS. Uptime, so if you're on a laptop, it's only when it's awake, you have to go through I talk about it in a second you have to go through and turn off like the go to sleep settings and all that So I use one of my gaming monitors for the Mac mini and then I just have it hooked into that So I can just turn it off, turn off the monitor and it's still running. So I like that with a laptop. You have to have it open all the time. I don't like that. So that's why I went the Mac mini route. It was just for me. And that's what works best for me. You have to figure out what works best in your workflow. PC when it's on and not sleeping, same thing. You got to turn off those settings. VPS 24-7, 365. But you pay for that. You have to pay for that service. And you should be probably spending like a DigitalOcean droplet, I think is like six bucks for the smallest one. If you go up a little bit from there, if you start hitting some issues with CPU usage, if you're running multi-agents and doing that whole workflow, then you might have to bump it up a couple of dollars to have a bigger droplet, etc. So that's just something to consider. Setup is easy on Mac. Native Unix, Homebrew, everything. A little bit, there's some node quirks in PC and medium on VPS. You need to understand SSH keys. You need to understand those basic Linux admin basic needs. You have to set up an environment and do stuff like that. Monthly costs is just the hardware and your electricity, hardware and electricity, five to 50 a month, depending on how big of, um, like a, a server that you set up or you can use AWS or whatever it is that you want to use uh performance Like I not going to go through all this You can go through that um ideal uh use cases so personal automation workflow development and testing content creators like content work configuration really easy to set up i literally had it set up immediately it was super simple um you know easy to kill the environment easy to manage internal like i'm just a i'm a mac guy when it comes to programming and pc when it comes to gaming and and that's just it is what it is. That's what, um, works for me, right? Um, common issues, uh, the going to sleep, uh, port conflicts, you can run into port conflicts, uh, change a port to your environment and do that node version mismatches. Um, uh, I think it's running on like node 22 right now. So you just have to run that prompt in, uh, you know, run the command in terminal and it'll upgrade node for you and then be able to run. I haven't run into any of these other issues because I'm on the newest Apple Silicon. So I don't really know about those issues, but those could be issues. File permissions, pretty easy to manage. You know, not too hard. Network timeouts with APIs. I mean, it is what it is. PC, budget conscious developers, dual purpose machines might be a gaming PC at night again I didn't want to do that like I like my gaming PC just running like I literally only run one game on my gaming PC and then my racing simulator is a PC and that's in the garage and that only runs one thing it just does racing so like I keep everything compartmentalized so there's no like sharing of documents and then my laptop is where I do all my important stuff and as my credit cards and whatnot so but that just how I keep everything separate a couple issues there you can run into common issues how to overcome them so forth So running a VPS on a Linux server you can read through this you know issues that you might be running into. And, you know, things to understand as you're planning and setting up your system configuration, like these are just some things to understand. And I give some SSH connection issues and some memory issues and, um, yeah, so forth. So I haven't run into any issues in trying to deploy it, um, you know, on a VPS, but, uh, you might run into those. So local Mac PC, you should be able to run multi-agents. Um, like I said, uh, when tasks spin up, I spin up like 12 sub agents and it runs perfectly fine. Like I think that I could run four at the same time in the same machine, but the crons might overlap. I don't know. So I'll figure it out. I'll get there to figure out how to scale it because I eventually want to get a Mac studio and do more all at the same time. But honestly, the 24 gig RAM Mac mini is really working out really well for me. I could have waited longer and gotten higher. I think 48 was the next jump up, but I didn't want to wait. I just wanted to get started on this. So yeah, it's just some quick checklist of what you need to do and some requirements that you need to do. Some of this stuff is just handled locally, but you have to do all of this when you're running on VPS. So that's just something to keep in mind. So I want to share this with you just to have that discussion about, I know a couple of people were asking about it, Mac versus PC versus VPS. Hopefully this answers your question and let me know if you have any other questions on it.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\MissionControlLesson\\transcription.txt:1:Let's talk about it. So this is the Mish Control dashboard that I built and I want to tell you guys this is not a small task. This is more than a week project running autonomously 24-7 to build this because you have your front end, your back