so understanding uh zoomed in understanding your structure so you're going to have project folders that's going to be for a business or a client or if you have multiple businesses if you just have one business and it'll be one project folder. Then you'll have tasks inside of that folder. So you could have cold outreach, you could have blogging, SEO, customer support, whatever. Then each model is going to be trained for the task of which it needs to do. Again, I like Haiku for the quick tasks, Sonnet for the more complex, Opus for strategy and if things are broken, etc so I don't like using Opus as much as possible and I like my action like if you gonna use Opus just go to you know the login and just use it from the web don use your agent for doing research or things like that that when you can do it on your paid account et cetera So you not expensing tokens on something that you could just do separately. But the ongoing efforts, I absolutely want Haiku and Sonnet to work hand in hand for that. So structuring everything is so important. So each task is done and your model is trained, your agent is trained based upon which model you're running. And then you set up each one of those project folders. You can put context inside your project folders as well to give that persistent memory across there, which is something your agent will probably do with creating these project folders and using these prompts. So I'm giving you the prompts to set up your project folders. You'll have to take this and edit it based upon what your business is and what your project name is and what the responsibilities are. So you have to take this, put it into a text editor and make sure that you have it perfectly summed up as per your use cases. And then as you go through, you can set up, you are a founder, an owner, a content creator, a dev, whatever it is that you do, you'll define what those use cases would be as putting into the prompt and customizing that prompt. Then from there, you're going to set up your task folders. So you're going to give it each individual task type. And then you're starting to give it specifics on what it is that it needs to do. Giving, you know, the correct output and the bad output, what you're wanting, what you're not wanting. And you can define that out a little bit more to give further context. And it's going to add that into the context files for each project and each task that you have. And then these context files will live outside of your core memory. So therefore it will not really expense too much each time because if you put everything in one memory file in the context then it going to be uploading it every single time but if you could put it into the project and then tell your agent on your core memory to check the the specific project when it's when it's running through a task then it'll go back and check that persistent memory and so forth ready to use task folder prompts so you can use these. Here are some examples for cold outreach. I know we're going to do each one of these tasks separately in a video coming up, but I'm just giving you some prompts that you can start using now that you can start this activity and get things going. Social media content planning, SEO and blogging, customer support management, UGC writing scripts, so forth, so many different things. But this is the area that I wanted to get into where you can start training your agent for because in order to have your agent do this, you have to have multiple projects already, you have to have multiple tasks, then you can ask your open claw to spin up multiple agents as well. And then each agent can know what it is it needs to do. Like haiku would be like those repetitive tasks, like scraping the internet or doing those types of things, give you some examples of those. and then the hierarchy of how you would split things off. Now inside of here, now we have the routing prompts. So now you have, you know, Haiku, Sonnet, Opus, whatever, handles this task with this folder and this is what you do, etc. So this is a prompt that you can use. And again, put it into a text editor and then, you know, fill in what it is that you need to do and what your project name is and what the task is. Then you can start making this folder, this structure, and then assigning an agent based upon what it is that agent needs to do. So you'll be able to route through there. So here a full walkthrough exactly how it done step by step You going to set up the project set up the task set up the task folder configure your router and then be able to test and refine and go from there So those are the step by step of going and getting this set up. Now, going a little bit more advanced would be chaining between agents. And again, you can spin up sub agents. I had a couple of people in the YouTube video comment and be like, I had no idea you could set up sub agents. Yeah, you can have sub agents running like Haiku could be doing your web scraping and Sonnet is just sitting there waiting. And then as the data comes in, your Sonnet would know CSV is, you know, set up. Now grab that and start writing, you know, context based upon what it is that it found. And it can start writing your outreach emails and start doing that that has a little bit more advanced reasoning. So you're setting it up to say, you know, hey, you're just doing the writing. So it's only going to take X amount of tokens. And then the web scraping is like really heavy. You're taking a lot of time in web scraping. So you're using Haiku for that, which is definitely going to be a lot more activity. So like 85% is like Haiku when I'm running tasks like that. So then you have your quality control agent. And then you can, you know, set this up for your QA. and then all of that optimization should be like super optimized and so forth. Again, I'll link to the video on YouTube if you didn't go through it. I know a lot of you did, but if you haven't gone through it, I really want you to go through it so you better understand how we're putting this piece together. But I wanted to give you guys these prompts, so I'll link below to this guide and set up your projects, your tasks, and then your tasks routing with the multiple agents. And again, if you have any issues, I'll link to the email below and we can definitely work through those blocks. So this is setting up multiple agents, multiple projects, multiple tasks, and then routing between each one of those. Let me know how it goes.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\SecyrityHardeningLesson\\OpenClaw-Security-Hardening-Guide-With-Agent-Prompts.docx.pdf:4:<</Title (OpenClaw-Security-Hardening-Guide-With-Agent-Prompts.docx)\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\SecyrityHardeningLesson\\transcription.txt:1:All right, here's the Open Claw Security Hardening Guide. I have copy and paste prompts in here. So I have how to use this guide, walks you through that. Purple boxes are prompts and green boxes are pro tips. So hardening assessment. First, we're going to do an assessment and an audit checklist. So you have this prompt here. We're going to scan the entire code base for hard-coded API keys, secrets, passwords, tokens, any of that. We need to check for it. So we're going to list everything using the agent. We're going to list all the environments that are currently set up, all the API endpoints for each application. And we're going to go through any common security, you know, misconfigurations, and it'll output any threats that we have. So if your agent finds any API hard-coded keys anywhere, stop. We're going to fix that immediately. So walking through, I'm not going to read everything on here. You can go through this yourself. So here's the breakdown of problems. Critical is like API theft. Prompt injection, we're going to harden for that. Model abuse, webhook hijacking, rate limit bypasses, other issues like that. So we're going to run through this. I have this scoring yes, no. And if you score 70 plus, that means you have a solid foundation. 50 below, you have some critical gaps. So kind of a scoring system for you to go through. So API keys, this is one of the big ones that you need to do. So here's your agent prompt. This will move those API keys and it will move them into secure environments. And then we're going to protect that environment. So, yeah, I understand you can still get hacked this way. You know, people can still hack your computer like anything can be hacked. So I don't want to hear it like, you know, this isn't going to make it secure, whatever. Like security is not guaranteeing that somebody isn't going to hack you. All security is doing is making sure that like the easiest ways for them to hack you, you're kind of locking those down and setting some rules and some guidelines to understand if you've had somebody hack you. So listen, like, you know, we're not talking about the $10 billion a year that Apple pays to security. We not talking about you know bank level security like a rate to this in terms of like the highest security Are we going to be bank-level encryption, yada, yada, yada? No, we're not. But are we going to be totally unsecure with API keys that are exposed, hard-coded? No, we're not going to do that either. We're going to fall somewhere in the middle and make this work. So just giving you that understanding, like when you say the word security, does it mean that this is like bank level encryption? No, it's not. So it's you're never going to get there with it. But, you know, we can definitely protect you by going through this. So secret scanning. So we're going to look for secrets. We're going to look for any exposed secrets. So you have a prompt for that authentication and access control. This will help with your login and all of that. So you're going to audit all those API routes and look at those JWT tokens and, you know, go through all of that to make sure that you have some level of security and you're not just, you know, admin is email and password is this. That's not going to be hard coded in there. And if it is, we're going to make sure it's not right. And also, like this is kind of like one on one security type stuff. And I understand a lot of you are just getting into OpenClaw as like your first kind of app deployment. And this is a good guide, something to go through. And, you know, for those people who are like serious security experts, like I have security experts on my team. I pay security experts to do this stuff for me. So am I like a 10 out of 10 security expert? Probably not. Am I an 8 out of 10? Maybe, maybe a 7. But I have like the top guys and I had them look through this and they're like, yep, that's solid. Send it. So role based control. Like we want to make sure that, you know, your app doesn't have full admin control over everything. If you have different levels and so forth, like we want to make sure it doesn't have control over everything. I did this and it locked it down to the point of which now, if I'm asking my agent to go in and write things in my config, it's like, I can't even read your config file. So it good from that point of view that my agent can prompt inject However now I have to go and make edits manually in my config file and so forth But I locked it down pretty hard for mine Just giving you that understanding So session management, you'll go through that prompt. Network security, you can go through this, enforcing a TLS security on it. And course is important to make sure that you can't get any prompt injections or anything like that. So we're going to lock down anyone being able to come in that way. So of course, I'll help out with that. Firewall and IP, like you don't have to do all of these if it is something that you're really serious about. Like, okay, so I am building a local, I'm going to share this. I'm building a local Google home that I am working on building the hardware for it to have like a Google home, but it's my agent that I'm leaving my kitchen. So I'm going to have to expose my internal network, but an internal IP that it can connect to my bot from inside of my home. I don't want it to connect outside of my home. So I'm going to lock it down that way, but I'm going to poke a hole kind of in my firewall, if you will, to ensure that my local machine is able to connect on my local network. Now, my concern is I have other things on my local network, like my ring and other things on my local network. So I don't want to expose my other devices on my local network if I'm giving access. So I want to lock it down and then make sure that I have an authentication with the token from my other local bot that I'm going to be creating that can connect directly into my bot that is running from my home. So just giving you some understanding, like there are levels that you can do to this and you can create access points, but you need to be mindful of how you're opening yourself up with the changes that you're making to, you know, your local connections and your your router and different things like that. So definitely things to keep in mind. So, yeah, we have that there as well. Rate limiting abuse So you can go ahead and add this This will help out with you know any issues that if it going out and there rate limit problems or different tokens per minute This is another thing that helped me to lock down because initially I had my rate limit like $30,000 was my rate limit for Anthropic and I got it raised to $450,000. So I added this on to make sure that I internally am now adding a rate limit and it's not, you know, I can't burn through $450,000 in a single prompt because something's broken or something's wrong. some other cost circuit breakers. I've added some of these thresholds. And this is another point that's like forcing my token audit, like because I do this token audit after every single task to make sure that, you know, when we plan out a task, I have it give me a token audit of how many tokens it expects to expense during that task that I'm asking it to do. And then also it'll prompt back to me after to say how many tokens it did use. So therefore I'm able to set some of these limits to make sure that I don't break in, um, and, and go like, you know, thousands of dollars a day, um, you know, pushing out these tasks and so forth. Prompt injection defense. So this is another point that'll help out with the prompt injections, logging, monitoring incident reports. So I have these logs and I haven't had any issues. So I guess I could kind of initiate like, you know, an attempted break or attempted problem. But I do get these updates in my system now. I asked it like once a week to give me like any monitoring or something like that. Like I'm not asking for like daily updates or anything. Incident report playbook. So I have this prompt as well. And again, this goes really, really deep. And you don't have to do every single thing in here. You can pick and choose what makes the most sense to you or if you're having issues, you can come back to this. But I wanted to give you guys this as a complete breakdown of all the things you could be doing and give you like this master checklist. So this is the hardening security. Hopefully this is helpful. Let me know and let me know how I can help out if you're having any issues. But here's the final agent prompt to go through and make a double check. And that should hard and so forth. But I locked it down pretty hard for mine. Just give it a little bit.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\SessionCommandMaessengerServicesLesson\\openclaw_token_guide.docx.txt:14:When you connect OpenClaw to a messenger platform like WhatsApp, Telegram, Slack, or Discord, the agent compiles ALL previous message history and sends it with every API call. This means each new message costs exponentially more tokens as the conversation grows. In the OpenClaw web app, there's a NEW SESSION button to clear this out - but messenger integrations don't have that button.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\SessionCommandMaessengerServicesLesson\\openclaw_token_guide.docx.txt:151:In OpenClaw, these files map to your agent's knowledge base or context files. Upload identity.md and context.md as persistent context documents. The agent will reference them on every call without stuffing them into conversation history.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\SessionCommandMaessengerServicesLesson\\transcription.txt:1:Hey, it's Matt, still going strong. Got another guide here for you. Let's go, let's zoom in on this. All right, so the Messenger Session Guide. So this is a walkthrough step-by-step on how to create, kill previous sessions. So each time you prompt, you're not uploading everything that you've ever said in Slack or Telegram or whatever. So OpenClaw, the way that it was built is the web interface has a button and that button is new session. And when you click that button, you clear the session. It still remembers who it is. It still remembers somewhat of what it was doing. And it still has like an understanding of what's going on. So Slack, Telegram, Discord, WhatsApp, iMessage, all these platforms. None of them have this in it. So when I realized this, I realized I had to make a prompt of a command to kill previous communication in order to remove it. Okay, let's go through this. So clear the command. So you have to create a command. So here is the prompt. Now, don't upload all of these. Pick one. Now, the thing that I found on Slack is that you can't use any slashes. I don't know about every platform, but on Slack, these are called slash commands and you can't use them. I tried to program it as a slash command but because it a web socket and because it was way too complicated So I was like almost done programming it And then I was just like, you know what? Forget it. Let's just come up with a word. The word that I had was new session because I would never say new session like this in any message that I ever send it. so I can't use hash values and I can't use slash commands. So it depends on your platform, but pick one of these. Like don't upload all of them. Pick one because you're going to have one command that when you say that command and it can't be something like, you know, start fresh. Like, I mean, I would make it one word, whatever, but make it something unique, like something, you know, not the word clear, not the word new, not the word reset, because you're going to say that you're going to say it normally in talking to it, but make it something that you would never say like one of these. It's up to you. And then we're giving it a clear directions on what to do. Immediately disregard all private conversations in context from this messenger thread. Do not reference, summarize, carry forward anything before the clear command. So we're telling it anything before. So if you're starting a brand new task, starting a brand new project, starting something brand new, you now have that kill word that you can prompt in your messenger. And that's what we're creating. Start fresh session. You know, how can I help right You can define whatever it is that you want this to be and begin next interaction with zero history and retain all uh only system prompts persistent memory files and project context C section two right So that something that we're going to be adding. Um, yeah, so all of that. And then if you have a webflow integration for some of your automation, like make or any end or whatever, uh, you'll need to program a kill in there as well because you're prompting it via webhook all right this is section two this is the persistent memory and you can load this up as well you maintain persistent memory through your project files so we're setting an identity in the project and a context in the project and we're setting these things in the project so this is what I was saying like if you're just building everything in dot open claw at the folder with your context files in there the issue is it's uploading those context files all the time so if they're really big then it's uploading every project that you ever did and that's the first way I set it up I had 14 projects in there and in all the tasks that they can do in projects so I was loading that up every time but when I split it and I put the context in the project folders, then when I direct it to the project to say get to work, it's reading the context in the project and not from the core memory. Make sense? So yeah, that'll prompt that to kind of explain what it is that it does and what it is that we're doing. Context compression prompt So again we want to compress maximum file sizes So this is something that will help compress now listen if you don have the project context set up and you not you haven done that yet don run this because this is going to compress like if you have some crazy long identity context task whatever if all of that is crazy long then yeah it's going to be an issue so yeah we we compress it afterwards Then after that, you have your tier one, tier two, tier three. So you have all these tiers of what it is that it's doing for each task. And this is the modeling. So this is the intelligent modeling as some people were asking for it. So I'll just drop it in here as well. And then I have a response link limiter, smart summarization before sign off or send off, whatever, deduplication guard. So we're not making the same API call twice. I was doing that. And I had two, like when you start setting up the subagents, you could have two agents say the same thing at the same time. So this will help. The schedule context pruning. So this will help audit that down. And here's your quick reference guide. So I put this together. The big thing from this is really section one and section two. So section one, you need to have a code word. You need to have a command that kills your previous sessions and you need to have persistent memory across projects. Those are the big things to take away from this. Get this installed and let me know if it fixes the problem.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\TokenCalibrationLesson\\OpenClaw_Token_Calibration_Guide.docx.txt:6:This is how you train your OpenClaw agent to accurately predict the cost of a task before it runs. The method is simple: ask it to guess, check the real number against your Anthropic dashboard, show it the difference. Repeat that a few times until the guesses are tight.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\updateOpenclawLesson\\OpenClaw_Update_Guide.docx.txt:95:~/.openclaw/workspace           # your agent workspace files\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\updateOpenclawLesson\\transcription.txt:1:Hey guys, how to update OpenClaw. So it's moving fast. There's a lot of changes that made OpenClaw a lot more stable, more secure, faster, a lot of things. So let me walk you through how to update. I just did the latest update and none of the configuration changes that I've given you with the multi-agent, the caching, none of them broke. So we're all set. So if you have the configuration and the memory and everything set up as I recommended, nothing is gonna break. So I had some concerns over this latest update. So we'll go through it real quick. So some performance highlights, again, giving you this document below the video. Some performance highlights, some security improvements, which is great. I mean we need more of that so I have a good feeling that they going to continue forward on making OpenClaw more stable over the next couple of months so it going to be fantastic Some channel updates that didn break anything with Slack or the service that I use So that's great. So that was awesome. This was the area that I was concerned about with the agency and memory improvements. And none of the updates, none of the changes that I've given you guys with the memory config changes or the multi-agents or the prompting cache or any of that, none of that has been damaged. And I confirmed it with my agent and also confirmed with Slack and then ran an update and ran the gateway doctor and nothing is broken. So definitely really good, really good things there. So a couple of things about the update, you can know which install that you have, run that prompt, definitely back up your config. that's really smart to backup configs. If you have your API keys in an environment file, then you would back that up, but that shouldn break anything So just giving you that context So it recommending to run this reinstaller If you do that you can add this no onboard and it skip the onboarding wizard But you honestly, you don't even need to do this. They recommend this. So I put it in there as recommended, but you could just run it via this command open claw update, really simple. And it ran after it runs follow up with open claw doctor now if anything did break the doctor will show if something is broken in your config so that will definitely help and then if that comes back as everything's okay then run the open claw gateway restart and then after that you can always ask your open claw like hey run a diagnostic and make sure everything's fine mine was fine everything works so if you run into any issues again what i was just saying there if If you run into any issues you can always go through this rollback process to roll back if something breaks but nothing should break because we should have the same config you know as you gone through this course and everything that I told you that you can modify is still working So I know that some people are saying that cash prompting is no longer working. It 100% is working because I'm running it right now and it's working. So here's some troubleshooting steps. And if all else fails, you can, you know, run through this and so forth. So you should be all right. So just wanted to give you guys an update on how to update your open claw and we need to stay up to date on the latest version so I'll keep you guys updated in the community when you do need to run another update and I will tell you when to run the update and let you know after I've run the update to make sure that nothing breaks if something does break I'll fix it and then I'll let you know how to fix it so yeah run the update you should be all set so I'll post this up Thank you.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\macmini_workspace\\workspace\\AGENTS.md:78:The `.learnings/` folder is indexed in the `qmd` `openclaw-workspace` collection - use `memory_search` for agent memory, `qmd search` for learning logs and notes.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\macmini_workspace\\workspace\\MEMORY.md:58:2. Se n�o estiver: `~/.openclaw/scripts/start-agent-chrome.sh` + esperar 5s\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\macmini_workspace\\workspace\\MEMORY.md:86:- Sempre verificar `openclaw.json`  `agents.defaults.models` antes de spawnar\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\macmini_workspace\\workspace\\.git\\index:2:?,??#>`???b?8[Eka.learnings/LEARNINGS.mdi?=?x?i?=?w?a????FC?}?^t?%)?Z[w*?.openclaw/workspace-state.jsoni???8??Ii???8??I???? ?Jx????S???????\tAGENTS.mdi?=?s?i?=?s??????????m#C??\"&F?\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\macmini_workspace\\workspace\\.git\\index:17:2skills/self-improving-agent/refere